.com/ Hard Rock Memorabilia Gallery]\n* [http://mynorthwest.com/?nid=129&sid=281939 \"Seattle welcomes Hard Rock Cafe\"]\n\n{{Hard Rock Hotel and Casino locations|state=collapsed}}\n{{Food chains in Australia}}\n{{Restaurant chains in Ireland}}\n{{Food chains in Japan}}\n{{Food chains in Taiwan}}\n{{Food chains in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Fast-food chains of the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Hard Rock Cafe| ]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Davie, Florida]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurant franchises]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1971]]\n[[Category:Seminole tribe]]\n[[Category:Theme restaurants]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chain of restaurants}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Redirect|Hard Rock Hotel and Casino}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Hard Rock Cafe Inc.\n| logo = [[File:Hard Rock Cafe Logo.svg|180px|Hard Rock Cafe logo]]\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Casual dining]] [[restaurant]]s, [[casino]]s, [[hotel]]s\n| key_people =  [[James F. Allen (businessman)|Jim Allen]] (president/[[CEO]])\n| owner = [[Seminole Tribe of Florida]]\n| founders = [[Isaac Tigrett]]<br>[[Peter Morton]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1971|06|14|df=y}}<br />[[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| location = [[Davie, Florida|Davie]], [[Florida]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|locations =\n180 Restaurants, 24 Hotels, and 11 Casinos\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.hardrock.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Hard Rock Cafe Inc.''' is a chain of [[theme restaurant]]s founded in 1971 by [[Isaac Tigrett]] and [[Peter Morton]] in [[London]]. In 1979, the cafe began covering its walls with [[rock and roll]] [[memorabilia]], a tradition which expanded to others in the chain. In 2007, Hard Rock Cafe International (USA), Inc. was sold to the [[Seminole Tribe of Florida]] and was headquartered in [[Orlando, Florida]], until April 2018, when the corporate offices were relocated to [[Davie, Florida]].<ref name=\"owner\"/><ref name=\"contactus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardrock.com/corporate/contactus/|title=Contact Us|publisher=Hard Rock Cafe|accessdate=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102064757/http://www.hardrock.com/corporate/contactus/|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>  As of July 2018, Hard Rock International has venues in 74 countries, including 185 cafes, 25 hotels, and 12 casinos.<ref name=\"hartford\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20151214/NEWS01/151219967|title=Hard Rock sets 170-room DoNo hotel|last=Seay|first=Gregory|date=December 14, 2015|website=|publisher=Hartford Business Journal|access-date=|accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref>{{Needs update|date=November 2017|reason=This has not been updated since December 2015.}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Restaurants===\nThe first Hard Rock Cafe (HRC) opened on June 14th, 1971 at [Old Park Lane], [[Mayfair]], [[London]], under the ownership of two Americans, [[Isaac Tigrett]] and [[Peter Morton]]. Hard Rock initially had an eclectic decor, but it later started to display memorabilia.\n\nThe chain began to expand worldwide in 1982 with locations in (among others) [[Toronto]], [[Los Angeles]], [[San Francisco]], [[Chicago]], [[Paris]], and [[Berlin]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hardrock.com/corporate/history/ |title=Hard Rock History |publisher=Hard Rock Cafe |accessdate=March 16, 2012}}</ref> Hard Rock Cafe locations in the United States vary from smaller, more tourist driven markets ([[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]], [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee|Pigeon Forge]], [[Key West, Florida|Key West]], etc.) to large metropolises ([[Houston]], [[Philadelphia]], [[New York City]], [[Chicago]], [[Boston]], [[Washington, D.C.]], etc.). Hard Rock Cafe typically does not franchise cafe locations in the United States. All US cafes are corporate owned and operated, except for cafes in [[Tampa]] and [[Four Winds New Buffalo]] casino.<ref>[http://www.hardrock.com/locations.aspx/ Hard Rock Cafe Locations]. Retrieved May 10, 2012</ref> However, in the transition of the [[Las Vegas]] Hard Rock Hotel property originally owned and then later sold to Rank by founder Peter Morton, Morton retained hotel naming rights west of the Mississippi. When Morton sold his Las Vegas Hard Rock Hotel to the [[Morgans Hotel Group]], he also sold those naming rights, which then gave rise to two US franchised hotels (without cafes) in [[Albuquerque]] and [[Tulsa]]. The Albuquerque hotel no longer pays for the Hard Rock rights and reverted to its former name in June 2013. Additional casino hotels franchised from Morgan's were subsequently opened in [[Sioux City, Iowa|Sioux City]] and [[Vancouver]].\n\nIn 1990, [[The Rank Group]], a London-based leisure company, acquired [[Mecca Leisure Group]] and continued expansion of the concept in its geographic territory. Rank went on to purchase ''Hard Rock America'' from [[Peter Morton]] as well as ''Hard Rock Canada'' from Nick Bitove. After the completion of these acquisitions, Rank gained worldwide control of the brand. In March 2007, the [[Seminole Tribe of Florida]] acquired ''Hard Rock Cafe International, Inc.'' and other related entities from Rank for [[United States dollar|US$]]965 million.<ref name=\"owner\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/6216292.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=Seminole tribe in Hard Rock deal |date=December 7, 2006 |accessdate=March 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, anonymous members of the wait staff criticized the business because of its practice of paying them less than half the official minimum wage in the UK, with the business allocating [[Mandatory tipping|tips]] to staff to bring their salaries within the law. Most customers, it was argued, do not realize that they are subsidizing a low wage when they give the tip.<ref name=\"tips\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7513273.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=Hard Rock wages 'below minimum' |date=July 18, 2008 |accessdate=March 17, 2012 |first=Martin |last=Shankleman}}</ref>\n\n===Music memorabilia===\n[[File:Jon Bon Jovi guitar, Moscow Hard Rock Cafe. 2008.JPG|thumb|[[Jon Bon Jovi]]'s guitar on display at the cafe in Moscow]]\n\nHRC is known for its collection of rock-and-roll memorabilia. The cafes solicit donations of music memorabilia but also purchase a number of items at auctions around the world, including autographed guitars, costumes from world tours and rare photographs; these are often to be found mounted on cafe walls. The collection began in 1979 with an un-signed Red [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Lead II guitar from [[Eric Clapton]], who was a regular at the first restaurant in [[London]]. Clapton wanted management to hang the guitar over his regular seat in order to lay claim to that spot, and they obliged. This prompted [[Pete Townshend]] of [[The Who]] to give one of his guitars, also un-signed with the note \"Mine's as good as his! Love, Pete.\"<ref name=\"memorabilia\">{{cite web| url=http://memorabilia.hardrock.com/?item=047894| title=Townshend's Gibson Les Paul| publisher=Hard Rock Cafe| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> Hard Rock's archive includes over 80,000 items,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardrock.com/corporate/history.aspx|title=Hard Rock Corporate - Hard Rock History|publisher=|access-date=February 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117035427/http://www.hardrock.com/corporate/history.aspx|archive-date=January 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and is the largest private collection of Rock and Roll memorabilia in the world. Marquee pieces from the collection were briefly displayed in a Hard Rock museum named \"The Vault\" in [[Orlando, Florida]] from January 2003 until September 2004. After the closure, items were disbursed to various restaurant locations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2004-09-30-0409300059-story.html|title=HARD ROCK VAULT SLAMS DOORS FOR GOOD|last=Writer|first=Jerry W. Jackson, Sentinel Staff|website=OrlandoSentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The London Vault remains open and free to visitors, located in the retail Rock Shop of the original cafe.<ref name=\"museum\">{{cite web| title=The Vault| url=http://golondon.about.com/od/thingstodoinlondon/fr/TheVault.htm| publisher=About.com| author=Laura Porter| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Hard Rock Caf\u00e9 is also in possession of a [[Bedford VAL]] 3 axle coach used in the 1967 Beatles film [[Magical Mystery Tour (film)|''Magical Mystery Tour'']]. The vehicle was completely refurbished after filming. It is currently displayed in the US, but makes regular appearances in events in the UK, especially at the original Hard Rock Cafe in London. In 2001, a competition was run to win the actual bus, but it was never given away and remained with the cafe.\n\n==Expansion into other businesses==\n\n===Casinos and hotels===\n[[File:Hard Rock Hotel Macau 2009.jpg|thumb|Hard Rock Hotel [[Macau]]]]\n[[File:Hard Rock Cafe, Melaka.jpg|thumb|Hard Rock Cafe [[Melaka]]]]\nIn 1995, Peter Morton spent $80 million to open the Hard Rock Hotel near the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. A subsequent $100 million expansion in 1999 nearly doubled the hotel's capacity.<ref name=\"hospitality\">{{Cite web| title=The Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Las Vegas Selects Rainmaker Group Revenue Management| url=http://www.hospitalitynet.org/news/154000320/4042095.html| website=Hospitalitynet.org| date=June 22, 2009| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, Morton sold the [[Hard Rock Hotel and Casino (Las Vegas)|Hard Rock Hotel & Casino, Las Vegas]] to [[Morgans Hotel Group]] for $770 million, including the rights to the ''Hard Rock Hotel'' brand west of the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]], including [[Texas]], California, [[Australia]], and [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"morgans\">{{cite news| title=Morgans Hotel Group to buy Vegas Hard Rock for $770 million| url=http://articles.marketwatch.com/2006-05-11/news/30918252_1_morgans-hotel-group-hard-rock-hotel-peter-morton| date=May 6, 2006| author=Spain, William| work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]| publisher=marketwatch.com| accessdate=March 17, 2012| archive-url=https://archive.is/20130128141808/http://articles.marketwatch.com/2006-05-11/news/30918252_1_morgans-hotel-group-hard-rock-hotel-peter-morton| archive-date=January 28, 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> The hotel began another expansion in 2007 at a cost of $750 million. The project added 875 rooms in two towers and expanded meeting space.<ref name=\"expansion\">{{cite news| title=Hard Rock Hotel expansion hits another milestone| url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/feb/06/hard-rock-hotel-and-casino-expansion-hits-another-/| date=February 6, 2009| author=Finnegan, Amanda| work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]| publisher=lasvegassun.com| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> In March 2011, Morgans surrendered control of the property to partner [[Brookfield Asset Management]], citing the high debt on the property in the face of the economic downturn.<ref name=\"end\">{{cite news| title=Hard Rock Hotel management group ends its run with resort| url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/mar/02/hard-rock-hotel-management-group-ends-its-run-reso/| date=March 2, 2011| author=Green, Steve | work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]| publisher=lasvegassun.com| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> In April 2018, the Hard Rock Hotel in [[Las Vegas]] was sold to [[Richard Branson]] with plans to renovate the property under the [[Virgin Hotels]] brand.<ref>{{cite web|website=casinoreviews.co.uk|title=Business Mogul Richard Branson Buys Las Vegas Casino-Hotel|url=https://www.casinoreviews.co.uk/news/casino/business-mogul-richard-branson-buys-las-vegas-casino-hotel.html |date=12 April 2018 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nToday, the Seminole Tribe of Florida owns and operates all units except the Las Vegas, Sioux City, Tulsa, and Vancouver properties. In 2004, Hard Rock International and [[Sol Melia]] Hotels and Resorts launched Lifestar Hoteles Espa\u00f1a SL, a [[joint venture]] that intended to manage Europe's first Hard Rock Hotel in [[Madrid]], but it was never opened as a Hard Rock property upon the dissolution of the joint venture in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Milligan|first1=Michael|title=Sol Melia confident that ME brand will stand out from the crowd|url=http://www.travelweekly.com/Travel-News/Hotel-News/Sol-Melia-confident-that-ME-brand-will-stand-out-from-the-crowd/|website=Travel Weekly|accessdate=January 22, 2007}}</ref> The other joint venture hotels are in Chicago, New York, and San Diego (the San Diego property includes Hard Rock condominiums). Hard Rock also operates hotels and resorts in [[Orlando, Florida]] (a joint venture with [[Loews Hotels]]); [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]]; and [[Pattaya]], [[Thailand]], (a joint venture with Ong Beng Seng/Hotel Properties Limited). Hard Rock International continues to expand internationally (including hotels, casinos, resorts, and condominiums) through several joint ventures (Becker Ventures, Ong Beng Seng/Hotel Properties Limited and Loews Hotels), including hotels in Chicago, Bali, Orlando, [[Penang]], San Diego, Singapore, and planned openings in Abu Dhabi, Cancun, Dubai, Hungary, Panama, Punta Cana and Puerto Vallarta,<ref name=\"hotels\">{{cite web| url=http://blog.hardrock.com/post/2007/10/24/HARD-ROCK-INTERNATIONAL-AND-THE-LUCKIE-STREET-PARTNERS-ANNOUNCE-ATLANTA-HOTEL-DEVELOPMENT.aspx| title=Hard Rock International and the Luckie Street Partners Announce Atlanta Hotel Development| date=October 24, 2007| website=Hard Rock Cafe| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> as well as hotel-casinos in [[Seminole Hard Rock Hotel and Casino Hollywood|Hollywood, Florida]]; [[Seminole Hard Rock Hotel and Casino Tampa|Tampa, Florida]]; Las Vegas, Nevada; and [[Catoosa, Oklahoma]], just northeast of [[Tulsa]].<ref name=\"contact\">{{cite web| url=http://www.hardrockcasinotulsa.com/Pages/contactus.aspx| title=Contact Us| website=Hard Rock Cafe| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n(The Hard Rock Casino in Biloxi, MS is owned by Twin River Management Group, Inc.)\n\nThe Hotel Zoso in [[Palm Springs, California]] was converted into a 160-room Hard Rock Hotel and opened in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|author=Vincent, Roger|date=February 10, 2013|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/money/la-fi-mo-hard-rock-hotel-20130208,0,676090.story |title=Palm Springs hotel to be converted into Hard Rock outpost'|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hard Rock Hotel Palm Springs Announces Star-Studded Grand Opening Celebration Set for March 6th |url=https://globenewswire.com/news-release/2014/02/19/611625/10069140/en/Hard-Rock-Hotel-Palm-Springs-Announces-Star-Studded-Grand-Opening-Celebration-Set-for-March-6Th.html |accessdate=November 10, 2016 |work=GlobeNewswire |date=February 19, 2014}}</ref> A location in [[Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Atlantic City|Atlantic City, New Jersey]] was planned in 2010, but those plans were canceled in 2012;  however, in 2017, they acquired from [[Icahn Enterprises]] the closed [[Trump Taj Mahal]], which in 2018 was reopened as Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Atlantic City.<ref>{{cite news|author=Wittkowski, Donald|date=September 13, 2012|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/communities/atlantic-city_pleasantville_brigantine/hard-rock-casino-developers-scrap-atlantic-city-casino-project/article_3f40dfa0-fccf-11e1-96e3-001a4bcf887a.html |title=Hard Rock casino developers scrap Atlantic City casino project|work=The Press of Atlantic City}}</ref> All-inclusive resorts operate under the Hard Rock brand in the Dominican Republic and Mexico. In 2013, the [[Hard Rock Rocksino Northfield Park]] opened as a joint slot machine and track venture., near [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. Then in early 2019, it was announced that [[Jack Cincinnati Casino|JACK Cincinnati Casino]] in [[Cincinnati]] was sold for $745 million to [[Vici Properties]] and [[Hard Rock International]], with Vici acquiring the land and buildings for $558 million and Hard Rock buying the operating business for $187 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hard Rock takeover gives Jack Casino a new owner, new name. What about a hotel?|newspaper=Cincinnati Enquirer|author1=Sarah Brookbank|author2=Alexander Coolidge|date=April 5, 2019|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/money/business/2019/04/05/hard-rock-international-buying-jack-cincinnati-casino-and-turfway-park/3373923002/|accessdate=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref name=vici>{{cite press release|title=Vici Properties Inc. to acquire Jack Cincinnati Casino and lease to Hard Rock International|publisher=Vici Properties|date=April 5, 2019|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190405005151/en/|via=BusinessWire|accessdate=2019-04-10}}</ref> Hard Rock would lease the casino from Vici for $43 million per year, and would rebrand it as Hard Rock Casino Cincinnati.<ref name=vici /><ref>{{cite news|title=Hard Rock Entertainment purchases Turfway Park|newspaper=The Blood-Horse|date=April 8, 2019|url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/232992/hard-rock-entertainment-purchases-turfway-park|accessdate=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\nCanada had numerous restaurants but many of them closed, notably the one at Yonge-Dundas Square in May 2017, which had been the chain's second location, leaving just two in that country, Niagara Falls, Ont., and the Hard Rock Casino in Coquitlam, B.C.<ref>{{cite news|work=CBC|location=Toronto|title=Hard Rock Cafe Legacy|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/hard-rock-cafe-legacy-toronto-1.4024286}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hard Rock announced a new hotel in [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia, which will open in 2019. The company had plans to open in the biggest financial district in Colombia, the ''Centro Internacional'', but it revised those plans. The hotel will be located in the exclusive ''[[Zona Rosa de Bogot\u00e1]]'', home of luxury boutiques.\n\nIn July 2019, Hard Rock International announced plans for a casino in [[Rockford, Illinois]], about 75 miles west of [[Chicago]] along [[Interstate 90 in Illinois|I-90]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Braun |first1=Georgette |title=Hard Rock would be the 'best partner' for a Rockford casino, Cheap Trick guitarist says |url=https://www.rrstar.com/news/20190716/hard-rock-would-be-best-partner-for-rockford-casino-cheap-trick-guitarist-says |accessdate=30 September 2019 |work=[[Rockford Register Star]] |date=16 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Two other proposals were made for the city's lone casino license, but the city council only recommended the Hard Rock proposal to the Illinois Gaming Board, who will decide which site will get the license.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guerrerro |first1=Isaac |title=Hard Rock Casino is Rockford mayor's choice for only license |url=https://www.rrstar.com/news/20190930/hard-rock-casino-is-rockford-mayors-choice-for-only-license |accessdate=30 September 2019 |work=[[Rockford Register Star]] |date=30 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Sacramento at Fire Mountain opened adjacent to the [[Toyota Amphitheatre]] near [[Wheatland, California]].\n\nAlso in November, Hard Rock announced a new hotel in [[Sao Paulo]], [[Brazil]], in the heart of popular [[Paulista Avenue]].\n\nOther international locations include: \n* [[Hard Rock Casino Vancouver]], [[Coquitlam]], B.C., Canada\n* Hard Rock Hotel and Casino Punta Cana, Macao, Dominican Republic\n* Hard Rock Hotel Bali, Bali, Indonesia\n* Hard Rock Hotel Cancun, C\u00e1ncun, Mexico\n* Hard Rock Hotel Davos, Davos, Switzerland\n* Hard Rock Hotel Goa, Bardez, India\n* Hard Rock Hotel Ibiza, Islas Baleares, Spain\n* Hard Rock Hotel Panama Megapolis, Panama City, Panama\n* [[Hard Rock Hotel Penang]], Penang, Malaysia\n* Hard Rock Hotel Pattaya, Chonburi, Thailand\n* Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya, Puerto Aventuras, Mexico\n* Hard Rock Hotel Shenzhen, Shenzhen, China\n* Hard Rock Hotel Singapore, [[Resorts World Sentosa]], Singapore\n* Hard Rock Hotel Tenerife, Tenerife, Spain\n* Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta, Riviera Nayarit, Mexico\n* Hard Rock Hotel London<ref>Hard Rock Hotel London {{cite web | url=https://sites.google.com/view/cumberland-hotel-london/Great-Cumberland-Place/Hard-Rock-Hotel-London | title=sites.google.com}}</ref>, United Kingdom (co-located with Hard Rock Oxford Street restaurant)\n\n===Hard Rock Park===\n{{main|Freestyle Music Park}}\nIn March 2006, Hard Rock Cafe International announced that it had licensed the \"Hard Rock\" name to HRP Myrtle Beach Operations, LLC, to design, build, and operate a $400 million {{convert|150|acre|km2|adj=on}} theme park called Hard Rock Park. Hard Rock Park opened on April 15, 2008 in [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]]. The park was expected to draw an estimated 30,000 visitors per day, promised to create more than 3,000 jobs, and was billed as the largest single investment in South Carolina's history. It planned to feature a large concert arena and six zones with more than 40 attractions. HRP Myrtle Beach Operations, LLC, filed for [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11]] on September 25, 2008. The company hoped to re-open in 2009 after restructuring.<ref name=\"park\">{{cite news| title=S.C.'s Hard Rock Park files for bankruptcy after inaugural season| url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/news/2008-09-25-hard-rock-park-bankruptcy_N.htm| date=September 25, 2008| work=[[USA Today]]| publisher=usatoday.com| accessdate=March 16, 2012}}</ref> On January 2, 2009 after failing to attract a buyer with a minimum $35 million bid for over two months, Hard Rock Park asked a Delaware Bankruptcy Court to convert the filing to Chapter 7, triggering immediate liquidation of assets to pay off creditors, and closing the park.<ref name=\"sentinel\">{{cite news| title=Hard Rock Park requests liquidation| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2009-01-03/news/C3report03_1_verizon-wireless-make-verizon-alltel| work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]| date=January 3, 2009| publisher=Orlandosentinel.com| accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nNew owners renamed the venue [[Freestyle Music Park]] and planned to reopen retaining a music-theme, but without the Hard Rock name, by [[Memorial Day]], 2009. The park only operated one additional year and then closed, due to poor attendance.<ref name=\"costal\">{{cite news| title=Coastal business: Freestyle Music Park attorney sees better market| url=http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2011/02/08/1968407/coastal-business-freestyle-attorney.html| work=[[The Sun News]]| date=February 8, 2011| publisher=myrtlebeachonline.com| accessdate=March 20, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403032709/http://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/2011/02/08/1968407/coastal-business-freestyle-attorney.html| archive-date=April 3, 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Stadiums===\n{{main|Hard Rock Stadium}}\nIn August 2016, it was reported that the [[Miami Dolphins]]' stadium in Miami Gardens, Florida would be renamed [[Hard Rock Stadium]]. [[Super Bowl LIV]] will be held there on February 2, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/nfl/miami-dolphins/article96001322.html|title=Miami Dolphins' stadium gets a new name: Hard Rock|last=Jackson|first=Barry|date=August 16, 2016|website=Miami Herald|publisher=|access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Hard Rock Club''' is a sponsored bar at the [[Canadian Tire Centre]], with Hard Rock branding and memorabilia.<ref name=\"HardRockClub\">{{cite web |author1=Sens Communications |title=Rideau Carleton Casino and Senators announce exclusive collaboration |url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/news/rideau-carleton-casino-and-senators-announce-exclusive-collaboration/c-300781474 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=April 8, 2019 |date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> The stadium formerly housed Ottawa's first Hard Rock Caf\u00e9 when it opened as The Palladium on January 15, 1996, and for many years when it was known as the [[Corel]] Centre. The caf\u00e9 closed on August 8, 2002 and was replaced with the [[Frank Finnigan]]'s restaurant.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Corel Centre |title=Restaurants - Home of the Ottawa Senators Hockey Club (National Hockey League) |url=http://corelcentre.com:80/guestservices/restaurants.aro |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021207154702/http://corelcentre.com/guestservices/restaurants.aro |archivedate=December 7, 2002 |date=December 7, 2002 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since October 17, 2013, the restaurant is known as Chek Point, and is sponsored by [[SportChek]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Chris |title=Chek Point to open Thursday |url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/news/chek-point-to-open-thursday/c-21535 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |date=October 16, 2013}}</ref> The Hard Rock Club bar was announced on October 9, 2018 and opened near the former Hard Rock Caf\u00e9. The bar features memorabilia from over a dozen artists, restaurant-style seating, and dedicated stadium seating.<ref name=\"HardRockClub\"/>\n\n==Acquisition by the Seminole Tribe of Florida==\nOn December 7, 2006, [[The Rank Group|Rank]] sold its Hard Rock business to the [[Seminole Tribe of Florida]] for $965 million. Included in the deal were 124 Hard Rock Cafes, four Hard Rock Hotels, two Hard Rock Hotel and Casino Hotels, two Hard Rock Live! concert venues, and stakes in three unbranded hotels. Rank retained the Hard Rock Casino in London, and rebranded it the G Casino Piccadilly. The Hard Rock Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas was also not part of the deal, as it was sold by Peter Morton to Morgans Hotel Group in May 2006.<ref name=\"seattlepi\">{{cite news| title=Seminoles buy Hard Rock cafe| url=http://www.seattlepi.com/business/article/Seminoles-buy-Hard-Rock-Cafe-1221859.php| author=Adrian Sainz| date=December 7, 2006| work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]| publisher=seattlepi.com| accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref> The final takeover was mired in controversy, due to a payment clause in a contract with one casino developer, Power Plant Entertainment. Power Plant and the Seminoles announced a settlement in April 2007 which both sides called equitable.<ref name=\"power\">{{cite news| title=Seminoles, developer settle disputes| url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2007-04-18/news/0704170429_1_power-plant-entertainment-seminole-hard-rock-cordish| author=John Burstein| date=April 18, 2007| work=[[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]]| publisher=sun-sentinel.com| accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref> On January 8, 2007, Rank shareholders approved the Seminoles' $965 million offer. The Tribe announced it had finalized the deal on March 11, 2007.<ref name=\"final\">{{cite news| title=Seminole Tribe Finalizes Acquisition of Hard Rock International| url=http://www.hotels-stl.com/News032507.htm| work=PRnewswire| publisher=hotels-stl.com| date=March 11, 2007| accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2008, the Seminole Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Hollywood began \"Vegas-style\" table gambling in addition to the [[Slot machine#Slot machine classes|Class II]] [[Slot machine|slots]] already in operation. To win approval for the table games, which were barred under Florida law, the Seminole Tribe paid the [[Florida|State of Florida]] $100 million as part of a 25-year pact signed by Governor [[Charlie Crist]]. On July 3, 2008, the [[Florida Supreme Court]] ruled that the governor's agreement was unconstitutional, but table games continue to operate because the Federal Department of the Interior approved the now-invalid pact with the state.<ref name=\"vegas\">{{cite news| title=Florida Supreme court nixes casino pact| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008031664_apindiangaming.html| author=Brenda Farrington| agency=Associated Press| date=July 3, 2008| work=[[The Seattle Times]]| publisher=seattletimes.com| accessdate=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==List of locations==\n{{cleanup|reason=reflinks in table - full info needed|date=June 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable \" style=\"border:none;\"\n|-\n!Location (city)\n!Location (country)\n!Status\n!Established\n!Closed/Moved\n!Comments\n|-\n| [[London]]\n| {{nowrap|United Kingdom}}\n| Open\n| {{dts|June 14, 1971}}\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| <s>[[Toronto]]</s>\n| Canada\n| Closed\n| {{dts|June 23, 1978}}\n| {{dts|May 24, 2017}}\n| Now [[Shoppers Drug Mart]]\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles|<s>Los Angeles</s>]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|October 24, 1982}}\n| December 21, 2006\n| \n|-\n| [[Tokyo]] [[Roppongi]]\n| Japan\n| Open\n| {{dts|July 4, 1983}}\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n| [[New York City]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|April 12, 1984}}\n| {{dts|August 12, 2005}}\n| Relocated to Times Square\n|-\n| [[San Francisco]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|September 10, 1984}}\n| {{dts|August 26, 2002}}\n| Relocated to Fisherman's Wharf\n|-\n| [[Stockholm]]\n| Sweden\n| Open\n| {{dts|April 16, 1985}}\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n| [[Chicago]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|June 17, 1986}}\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n| [[Dallas|<s>Dallas</s>]]\n| United States\n| Closed\n| {{dts|November 6, 1986}}\n| {{dts|March 3, 2007}}\n| Relocated July 15, 2009. Closed July 31, 2019\n|-\n| [[Houston]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|November 6, 1986}}\n| {{dts|May 21, 2000}}\n| Relocated, closing permanently May 27, 2020\n|-\n| [[Canc\u00fan]]\n| Mexico\n| Open\n| {{dts|June 9, 1987}}\n| {{dts|March 19, 2016}}\n| Reopened\n|-\n| [[Honolulu]]\n| United States\n| Open\n| {{dts|July 15, 1987}}\n| {{dts|November 23, 2000}}\n| Relocated\n|-\n| [[Reykjav\u00edk|<s>Reykjav\u00edk</s>]]\n| Iceland\n| Closed\n| {{dts|July 25, 1987}}\n| {{dts|October 30, 2016}}\n| Closed May 29, 2005. Relocated\n|-\n| [[New Orlean