e blessing of Mother Gayatri, Vishwarath the warrior became Vishwamitra the sage. Lord Brahma himself proclaimed him as a high priest. King Satyavrat who was barred from entering Heaven alive was given a new Heaven by this great sage. Vishwamitras grandson Bharat became the founding father of 'Bharat Varsha'. He proved to the mighty Gods how virtuous a mere human being could be through the example of King Harishchandra.''\n\n''So much so, he was the one who made Ram & Laxman brave warriors. After Lord Rams marriage to Sita, sage Vishwamitra became one of the seven celestial sages. His life is unequalled, unique and indeed reverential.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dla.library.upenn.edu/dla/vcat/record.html?id=VCAT_3761598&|title=Vishwamitra (1995)|website=dla.library.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>''\n|}\n<br />\n== Episodes ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!''No.''\n!''Notes''\n|-\n|''1''\n|''Vishwarath anointed as the new King by his father.''\n|-\n|''2''\n|''He reaches [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s [[ashram]] with his army after a war. After getting exceptional hospitality in the ashram, he came to know about the divine cow Nandini. When a famine struck his kingdom he asks his counsel to get Nandini cow from [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]], which the later refuses.''\n|-\n|''3''\n|''Angry King Vishwarath reaches the ashram and tries to get the cow forcefully but failed. The humiliated king decides to gain divine power by doing [[Tapas (Indian religions)|tapasya]] and abdicates the throne for his son.''\n|-\n|''4''\n|''Vishwarath got the boon of various divine weapons from [[Brahma|Lord Brahma]]. He again reaches [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s [[ashram]] to capture Nandini but fails. He vows to gain more power by doing great penance to become a [[Brahmarshi|Brahmarishi]].''\n|-\n|''5''\n|''Ayodhya King Sathyavrata anoints his son Harishchandra as the new King and decides to ascend heaven with his mortal body. However, his unnatural wishes got refuted by [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]. He tried to lure [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s son Satya to help him achieve his desires. An angry Satya curses Sathyavrata and makes him [[Trishanku]].''\n|-\n|''6''\n|''Vishwarath after severe penance and tapasya gained more powers and blessing of Mother Gayatri, Vishwarath the warrior became Vishwamitra the sage.''\n|-\n|''7''\n|''A dejected [[Trishanku]] approaches Vishwamitra to achieve his desires. After knowing that [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] refused his wishes, Vishwamitra promises him the impossible. But his [[yajna]] got rejected by Indra and other gods.''\n|-\n|''8''\n|''Vishwamitra begins creating alternate heaven for Trishanku when gods dismiss him from Indra's heaven.''\n|-\n|''9''\n|''[[B\u1e5bhaspati]] (along with [[Narada]] ) tries to persuade Vishwamitra to abandon creation new heaven for Trishanku which he agrees. However, Narada later instigates him reminding the promise he made to Trishanku. Vishwamitra begins more penance to gain uninterrupted access to heaven. Knowing this Indra and other gods (on the advice of Brhaspati) decide to disrupt his [[tapasya]]. They create a celestial Mahashakti after uniting their powers. But he failed and Vishwamitra killed him with his divine powers.''\n|-\n|''10''\n|''[[Indra]] decides to disrupt Vishwamitra's penance by sending [[apsara]] Rambha to seduce him. But an angry Vishwamitra curses her and turned her into a rock. She regretted her actions and asked for forgiveness. He gave her the boon that in future she will be liberated by a Maharishi. After failing repeatedly, Indra decides to disrupt his tapasya himself and went to Vishwamitra disguising as a hungry brahmin. But Vishwamitra recognized him easily and still gave his divine food gained from penance. He embarrasses Indra for his malevolent deeds. A dejected and humiliated Indra leaves for heaven.''\n|-\n|''11''\n|''Upon advice of Brhaspati, Indra summons apsara [[Menaka|Meneka]] to seduce Vishwamitra. A reluctant Menaka agrees for the task. She decides to take help from [[Rati]] and [[Kamadeva|Kamadev]].''\n|-\n|''12''\n|''After severe attempts Menaka successfully gained the attention of Vishwamitra and made him fell in love with her.'' \n|-\n|''13''\n|''Both of them got married and thus Indra task finally got fulfilled. He then asks Menaka to return back to heaven but Menaka refuses as she's in love with Vishwamitra too. Indra orders her to return as it'll be unnatural for a celestial being to spend time on earth. A year later Menaka gave birth to a daughter. Narada reminds Indra that Menaka hasn't returned to heaven.'' \n|-\n|''14''\n|''Menaka finally confesses to Vishwamitra that she was sent on a mission by Indra and now as her task is complete she had to return. An angry and disheartened Vishwamitra abandons Menaka and his daughter and sets out to fulfill his vow to become a Maharishi. Menaka also ascended to heaven leaving their daughter behind. [[Rishi]] [[Kanva]] and his wife Gautami found the girl in the forest and adopted her. As a baby, she was surrounded by Shakunta birds ([[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]]: \u0936\u0915\u0941\u0928\u094d\u0924, \u015bakunta). Therefore, he named her Shakuntala (Sanskrit: \u0936\u0915\u0941\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0932\u093e), meaning Shakunta-protected.''\n|-\n|''15''\n|''King [[Dushyanta]] arrives in Rishi Kanva's ashram and fell in love with Shakuntala.''\n|-\n|''16''\n|''Shakuntala and Dushyant's love blossoms.''\n|-\n|''17''\n|''Dushyant proposes Shakuntala for marriage and they have a [[gandharva]] marriage. Having to leave after some time, Dushyant gives Shakuntala a royal ring as a sign of their love, promising her that he will come to her. One day, sage [[Durvasa]] visits the hermitage, but Shakuntala, who is too absorbed in her love for Dushyant, forgets to serve him food. In a fit of anger, sage Durvasa curses her, saying that the person she is thinking about will forget her.''\n|-\n|18\n|''Shocked friends of Shakuntala begs for forgiveness and the sage, after recollecting his calm, assures her that the person will remember her again when she shows some proof of their acquaintance. Her friends decide not to tell her anything about the curse. Shakuntala got pregnant and Rishi Kanva decides to send her to Dushyanta.'' \n|-\n|19\n|''So, Shakuntala sets off to the capital, [[Hastinapur]], to remind Dushyant of their past love. Dushyanta does not recollect Shakuntala and asks for proof but an accident occurs by which a fish consumes the royal ring, leaving Shakuntala with no formidable proof. A disheartened Shakuntala left the capital. Her mother Menaka helped her and took her to a sage's ashram so that she can give birth to the child. A fisherman brought the lost ring back to the King and his memory and love are rekindled.''\n|-\n|20\n|''Meanwhile, Shakuntala gave birth to [[Bharata (Mahabharata)|Bharata]]. One day King Dushyanta while hunting met Bharata & Shakuntala, and the couple is finally reunited. A meeting is called in heaven by Indra with combine participation of representatives of earth and heaven. All [[Brahmarshi|Brahmarishis]] are invited and [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] urges Indra to call Maharishi Vishwamitra too as he'll be soon a Brahamrishi. Narada is asked to invite Vishwamitra which he accepts. During the meeting, a discussion arises about the most valuable matter in the universe. [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] concluded that there is nothing more precious than truth. He also named Raja [[Harishchandra]] as the king who follows the difficult path of truth. His claim is challenged by Vishwamitra and he proposes to test Harishchandra's integrity.'' \n|-\n|21\n|''Vishwamitra reaches Harishchandra court and asks for an unusually huge amount of treasure for yajna purpose which the King readily accepts. Even upon insistence from the King and his counsel, Vishwamitra refuses to take the treasure at once and asks the king to set aside the treasure with himself and he will take it when the right time arrives. Later, Viswamitra creates and send wild animals to Harishchandra's kingdom to further test his mettle.''\n|-\n|22\n|\n|}\n\n== Music ==\nLyrics for various songs were written by Bhring Tupkari and music was composed by Vasu Rao. The title song was performed by [[K. J. Yesudas|Yesudas]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dla.library.upenn.edu/dla/vcat/record.html?id=VCAT_3761598&rotation=0&detail=staff|title=Vishwamitra (1995)|website=dla.library.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0262876}}\n\n\n[[Category:Indian mythological television series]]\n[[Category:1995 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Doordarshan television series]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Unclewalker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vishwamitra_(1995_TV_Series)"}
{"title_page": "Edward Lewknor (died 1556)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n'''Edward Lewknor''' (c.1517\u20131556) was the representative of a branch of a prominent Sussex family, in an [[armigerous]] line descending in the distaff side from the [[Baron Camoys|Camoys barony]]. Having attained standing as a member of parliament and (reportedly) a position of service in the royal household, his career was ended abruptly by his involvement in [[Henry Dudley (conspirator)|Henry Dudley]]'s conspiracy against Queen [[Mary I of England|Mary I]], and his consequent [[attainder]]. His children were restored in blood by Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]].<ref>For a referenced account of Edward Lewknor, see R.J.W. Swales, 'Lewkenor, Edward (1518\u201356), of Kingston Buci, Sussex', in 'Local Politics and the Parliamentary Representation of Sussex 1529\u20131558' (PhD Dissertation, University of Bristol 1964), Vol. 2, [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/29029355.pdf pp. 288\u2013291 (pdf p. 298)].</ref> \n\n==Family origins==\nEdward Lewknor<ref>R.J.W. Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward (1516/17-56), of Kingston Buci, Suss.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.) ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer, 1982) [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/lewknor-edward-151617-56 History of Parliament online].</ref> was the son of Edward Lewknor (died 1528) of [[Kingston by Sea|Kingston Buci]], Sussex,<ref>D.G.C. Elwes and C.J. Robinson, ''A History of the Castles, Mansions, and Manors of Western Sussex'' (Longmans & Co., London/G.P. Bacon, Lewes), [https://archive.org/details/ahistorycastles00elwegoog/page/n181 pp. 130\u201331].</ref> and his wife Margaret Copley, daughter of Roger Copley [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|citizen and Mercer]] of London and of Roffey (in [[Horsham, Sussex]] - died c. 1482<ref>Admitted to freedom of Mercers, 1456: see L. Jefferson, ''The Medieval Account Books of the Mercers of London: An Edition and Translation'', 2 vols (Ashgate, Aldershot 2009), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Bc8GDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT1105&lpg=PT1105&dq=%22Roger+Cople%22&source=bl&ots=6jrXxcbAww&sig=ACfU3U2sXnnoK1v4NXmKn8u8XNRQfZmxKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbr_G7xNbnAhXFoXEKHUclDxwQ6AEwAHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Cople&f=false Name Index] (Google).</ref>) by his wife Anne, a daughter and coheiress of Sir [[Thomas Hoo, Baron Hoo and Hastings]] by Eleanor, daughter of [[Lionel Welles, 6th Baron Welles|Lionel Welles]].<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'' 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8JcbV309c5UC&pg=RA1-PA9#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 8\u201310] (Google). Sir Thomas Hoo had two daughters named Anne: this was the younger.</ref> Margaret Copley's sister Eleanor was the third wife of [[Thomas West, 8th Baron De La Warr]], who acted as [[Feoffment|feoffee]] for Edward's grandfather in securing the descent and uses of his estates according to the terms of his will.<ref>Will of Edward Lewknor of Kingston Buci (P.C.C. 1528).  Inquisition post mortem: Edward Lewkenor (Sussex), T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 142/47/41 (Chancery).</ref> Edward's father had a younger half-brother Richard Lewknor and three half-sisters, whose mother Anne (died 1538),<ref>Will of Dame Anne Echingham (P.C.C. 1538).</ref> daughter of John Everard of [[Cratfield]] and sister-in-law of John Tasburgh of [[St Peter, South Elmham]],<ref>'Everard' (1), in W. Rye (ed.), ''The Visitations of Norfolk, 1563, 1589 and 1613'', Harleian Society Vol. XXXII (London 1891), [https://archive.org/details/publicationsofha32harluoft/page/116 pp. 116-17] (Internet Archive).</ref> remarried to Sir [[Edward Echyngham]] of [[Barsham, Suffolk]] (died 1527).<ref>Will of Sir Edward Echyngham of Barsham (P.C.C. 1527).</ref><ref>F.H. Suckling, 'Some Notes on Barsham juxta Beccles, co. Suffolk', ''The Genealogist'' XXI (1905), [https://archive.org/stream/genealogist2119selb#page/n269/mode/2up pp. 124-42], 243-50, and XXII (1906), [https://archive.org/stream/genealogist2219selb#page/n123/mode/2up pp. 52-61] (Internet Archive), 128-34, 149-54 and 212-22, '''at''' XXII, pp. 52-61.</ref>\n\n===The Camoys descent===\nHis grandfather, also Edward (died 1522),<ref>Will of Edward Lewkenour of Kingston Bowcy (P.C.C. 1522\u201323). The date of Probate shown in the Register is earlier than the date of the will itself, and should probably read 1523.</ref> was the son and heir of Nicholas Lewknor of Kingston Buci (youngest son of Sir Thomas Lewknor of [[Horsted Keynes]] by Elizabeth Echyngham, stepmother of Baron Hoo and Hastings) and his wife Elizabeth (Isabella) Radmylde.<ref>As shown in the ''Drury Manuscript'', British Library Add. MSS. 5523, fol. 110: see J.J. Howard (ed.), ''The Visitation of Suffolke, made by William Hervey, Clarenceux King of Arms, 1561,'' Vol. II (Samuel Tymms, Lowestoft/Whittaker & Co., London 1871), pp. 261\u201370, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LCgAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA269#v=onepage&q&f=false at p. 269.] W.D. Cooper, 'Pedigree of the Lewknor Family', ''Sussex Archaeological Collections'' III (1850), [https://archive.org/stream/sussexarchaeolo13socigoog#page/n132/mode/2up pp. 89\u2013102, at p. 102.]</ref> Elizabeth and her sister Margaret Radmylde became the coheirs of their nephew William Radmylde, who died without issue. Their mother Margaret Camoys (born c. 1402), first wife of Ralph Radmylde, was granddaughter of [[Thomas de Camoys, 1st Baron Camoys]] (died 1421), and (with her sister Eleanor) coheir to her brother [[Hugh de Camoys, 2nd Baron Camoys|Hugh Camoys, 2nd Lord Camoys]].<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Plantagenet Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), I, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kjme027UeagC&pg=PA471#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 471 ff.]</ref> Eleanor married Sir Roger Lewknor of Broadhurst, elder half-brother of Nicholas Lewknor.<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), III, 'Lewknor', pp. 15\u201321 at pp. 18\u201319, and see [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8JcbV309c5UC&pg=RA3-PA372#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 372.]</ref> Hugh died in 1426, when the title went into abeyance until 1839. It was then resurrected in [[Thomas Stonor, 3rd Baron Camoys]], descendant and heir of Elizabeth Radmylde's sister Margaret, who married John Goring.<ref>C. Clark and W. Finnelly, ''Reports of Cases Heard and Decided in the House of Lords on Appeals and Writs of Error, and Claims of Peerage: During the Sessions 1831[-1846],'' Vol. 6, 1838 & 1839 (V. & R. Stevens and G.S. Norton, London 1842), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GmBGAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA789#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 789\u2013867; see p. 818.]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Hamsey, St Peter's Church.jpg|thumb|right|300|St Peter's church, Hamsey, Sussex]]\nLewknor had a younger brother Anthony and sisters Eleanor, Mary and Barbara.<ref>W. Bruce Bannerman, ''The Visitations of the County of Sussex... in 1530 and 1633\u201334, etc.'', Harleian Society LIII (London 1905), [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n45/mode/2up pp. 25\u201330, at pp. 28\u201329.]</ref> According to an Inquisition upon his father's death,<ref>Chancery, C 142/47/41.</ref> Edward was then 11 years old. His father's will, however, left estates including [[Hamsey]] (East Sussex) in feoffment to mature for him in October 1542. Other estates including Kingston Buci were allocated to Anthony, and were in the administration of the widow and three other executors, and with the assistance of Sir Roger Copley, during minority. Margaret Lewknor assumed sole responsibility as [[executor]] but Edward came into the wardship of one of the co-executors, Robert Wroth of Durrants, [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]] (Middlesex), and of [[Gray's Inn]]<ref>Autumn reader, 1528: J. Foster, ''The Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn, 1521\u20131889'' (Hansard, London 1889), [https://archive.org/stream/registerofadmiss00gray#page/2/mode/2up p. 2.]</ref> (from 1531 attorney of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] and M.P. for Middlesex 1529\u20131535), a descendant of Sir Roger Lewknor and Alianora Camoys.<ref>'Wroth of Enfield', in G.J. Armytage (ed.), ''Middlesex Pedigrees collected by Richard Mundy'', Harleian Society LXV (1914), [https://archive.org/stream/middlesexpedigre651914#page/16/mode/2up p. 17.] Richardson, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', III, p. 372.</ref>\n\nRobert Wroth's eldest son [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 16th century)|Thomas Wroth]] was of a very similar age to Edward Lewknor.<ref>H. Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas (1518\u201373), of Durants, Enfield, Mdx. and London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wroth-thomas-1518-73 History of Parliament online]</ref> The Wroth household was of Protestant sympathy: Robert Wroth became a friend of [[Thomas Cromwell]]'s, and from 1534 until his death two years later Wroth shared with Cromwell the stewardship of Westminster Abbey.<ref>H. Miller, 'Wroth, Robert (1488/89-1535), of Durants, Enfield, Mdx.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wroth-robert-148889-1535 History of Parliament online]</ref> Thomas was sent to [[St John's College, Cambridge]], but did not take a degree.<ref>J. & J.A. Venn, ''Alumni Cantabrigienses'' I.iv (Cambridge University Press, 1927), [https://archive.org/stream/p1alumnicantabri04univuoft#page/468/mode/2up pp. 468\u201369.]</ref> At his father's death in 1536 he became a ward of the Crown, and in that year he entered Gray's Inn.<ref>Foster, ''Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn'', p. 11.</ref> It is claimed (but does not appear) that Lewknor was admitted in the same year.<ref>R. Chapman, 'The Parochial History of Hamsey', ''Sussex Archaeological Collections'' XVII (George P. Bacon, Lewes 1865), pp. 70\u2013103, [https://archive.org/stream/sussexarchaeolo21socigoog#page/n106/mode/2up at p. 79.]</ref> Cromwell at once obtained a grant of the marriage and wardship of Thomas Wroth,<ref>J. Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic'', Henry VIII, Vol. XI (HMSO 1888), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol11/pp349-378 943: Grants October 1536 (item 6).]</ref> and in 1538 sold the marriage to [[Richard Rich, 1st Baron Rich|Sir Richard Rich]], who arranged that Thomas should marry his daughter Mary Rich.<ref>Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers'', Henry VIII, XIV (ii), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol14/no2/pp303-358#highlight-first Miscellaneous: December 1538 & May 1539, p. 324]; XV, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol15/pp251-300#highlight-first 613: Grants April 1540 (item 9)], [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol15/pp325-349#highlight-first 733: Grants May 1540 (item 64)]. (British History Online)</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nThe wardship and marriage of Edward were granted to his mother in May 1533.<ref>Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers, Henry VIII'' VI, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol6/pp234-262#highlight-first 578: Grants May 1533 (item 37).]</ref> However Robert Wroth in his will written in 1535 explicitly required that his ward Edward Lewknor should marry his daughter Dorothy: if either were to refuse or mislike the match, Dorothy was to have the financial benefit arising from the dissolution of the wardship.<ref>Will of Robert Wroth of Durrants, Enfield (P.C.C. 1536).</ref> Edward and Dorothy were accordingly married. Dorothy's mother Jane was the daughter of Sir Thomas Hawte (a [[William Hawte|Woodville]] descendant), who had died in 1505, and his wife Isabel (Elizabeth) Frowyk, sister of [[Thomas Frowyk|Sir Thomas Frowyk]].<ref>R. Hovenden (ed.), 'De Haut', ''The Visitation of Kent taken in the years 1619\u20131621 by John Philipot and William Camden'', Harleian Society XLII (London 1898), pp. 212\u201314, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationofkent00camd#page/214/mode/2up at p. 214.]</ref><ref>Richardson, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', II, p. 9.</ref> The union reinforced existing ties of kinship among the numerous posterity of Sir Thomas Lewknor, and reinvested two Camoys lines. The manor of Kingston Buci was in 1537 settled upon Margaret Lewknor for life with an additional twenty years' tenure with remainder in tail male to Anthony Lewknor. Anthony was admitted to Gray's Inn in 1542.<ref>Foster, ''Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn'', [https://archive.org/stream/registerofadmiss00gray#page/8/mode/2up p. 15.]</ref>\n\nMargaret Lewknor lived until at least 1551,<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece descriptions Holmes, Campbell & Co/983 and /1084 (West Sussex Record Office).</ref> and was no doubt instrumental in arranging the marriages of Edward's sisters. Eleanor became the wife of Giles Sentbarbe, Rector of Hamsey c. 1541\u20131555.<ref>Church of England Clergy database: Giles or Egidius Sayntbarbe, Sentbridge, Senbar, etc.: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/locations/index.jsp?locUnitKey=14358 parish of Hamsey.]</ref> Mary married John Michell the younger of Stammerham (in Horsham),<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Horsham: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex''  Vol. 6 Part 2: Bramber Rape (North-Western Part) Including Horsham, (V.C.H., London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt2/pp156-166#anchorn264 pp. 156\u201366.]</ref> a resident of Horsham, whose parliamentary connections may have assisted Lewknor's own ambitions.<ref>R.J.W. Swales, A.D.K. Hawkyard, 'Michell, John II (died 1555), of Stammerham, Suss.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: The House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/michell-john-ii-1555 History of Parliament online.]</ref> Lewknor's sister Barbara married Sir John Dawtrey.\n\n==Progress==\n[[file:Primero.jpg|right|thumb|''Four Gentlemen of High Rank Playing Primero'' (16th century).]]\nThe marital existence of Edward and Dorothy Lewknor was fruitful, producing ten children,<ref>S. D'Ewes, ''The Journals of all the Parliaments During the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vA1DAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49, col. 2, 3 March 1558/9.] Howard, ''Visitation of Suffolk'', II, p. 269, note.</ref> of whom the eldest of the four sons, Edward, was born c. 1541\u201342. It is inferred that the elder Edward entered the service of the [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]].<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament''.</ref> He is suspected to be the Lewkenor, one of the Duke's gentlemen, who in December 1545 came to blows with [[Thomas Hussey (died 1558)|Thomas Hussey]] of Caythorpe, M.P., treasurer to the Duke, while gambling at cards 'at Domyngo's house' in a game of [[primero]].<ref>S.M. Thorpe and T.M. Hofmann, 'Hussey, Thomas I (by 1509\u20131558), of Halton Holegate and Caythorpe, Lincs.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), \"The History of Parliament: The House of Commons 1509\u20131558\" (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/hussey-thomas-i-1509-58 History of Parliament online.]</ref> The affray occurred at Tothill Fields behind the old [[Palace of Westminster#Old Palace|Palace of Westminster]]: Hussey was reprimanded by the [[Privy Council]], since parliament was sitting at the time, and he (and perhaps also Lewknor) ought to have been there. Both men were briefly committed to the [[Fleet prison]].<ref>S.E. Lehmberg, ''The Later Parliaments of Henry VIII'', 1536\u20131547 (Cambridge University Press, 1977), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MhY9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA228#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 228.]</ref>\n\n[[Henry Machyn]] stated Edward Lewkenor to have been [[Groom Porter]] to King [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]],<ref>J.G. Nichols (ed.), ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', Camden Society Old Series XLII (London 1848), [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/108/mode/2up pp. 108, 114.] Machyn calls him 'master Lecknolle'.</ref> a fact lacking positive confirmation from other sources. (This office included responsibility for royal games at cards). Thomas Wroth, who was knighted in 1547, was successively Gentleman Usher to the Prince's Chamber (1541\u20131547), [[Gentleman of the Privy Chamber]] (1547\u201349) and a principal Gentleman (1549\u201353) to the King: he was also [[Knight of the Shire]] for [[Middlesex (UK Parliament constituency)|Middlesex]] in the parliaments of 1547, 1549 and March 1553.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament online''.</ref> Lewknor is likely to have gained his position in the royal household through his brother-in-law's connections and the influence of Richard Rich.\n \n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Bramber Castle.jpg|thumb|right|300|Bramber Castle seen by [[Wenceslas Hollar]] (1607\u20131677)]]\nIn 1548 Margaret Lewknor was the demesne lessee of the manor of High Barns at [[Upper Beeding]], Sussex,<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Upper Beeding: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex''  Vol. 6 Part 3: Bramber Rape (North-Eastern Part) Including Crawley New Town, (V.C.H., London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt3/pp34-37#anchorn19 pp. 34\u201337.] (British History Online. Retrieved 19 November 2016)</ref> a property seized by the Crown from the attainted Duke of Norfolk, which had been granted to [[Thomas Seymour, 1st Baron Seymour of Sudeley|Thomas Seymour]] in 1547. Following Seymour's attainder in 1549, on 21 May 1553 it, together with the site of the former [[Bramber Castle]] and the disparked lands called Le Newe Park at Upper Beeding were granted in chief by the King to Edward Lewknor, King's Servant, Esquire, for the fortieth part of a knight's fee and in consideration of \u00a3718.8s.8d paid to Sir Edmund Peckham on behalf of the King.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Edward VI, V: 1547\u20131553'' (HMSO, London 1927), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027026412&view=image&seq=108 p. 102] (Hathi Trust).</ref> Lewknor was also granted the house of the former Butler Chantry ''cantarista'' in Horsham, and several tenements appertaining to it, in free socage. The acquisition of the site at Bramber was no doubt a visible assertion or impropriation of Lewknor's perceived [[William de Braose, 1st Lord of Bramber|de Braose]] ancestry or forebears.<ref>Lewknor was descended from [[Thomas de Camoys, 1st Baron Camoys]] (died 1421). The ''Liber Drury'' Lewknor pedigree represents the mother of Camoys as Margaret Foliot (daughter of Joan de Braose), and his paternal grandmother as Margaret de Braose, wife of Ralph de Camoys (died 1336). In both cases Camoys is now understood to have been descended from other wives than these. De Braose is included in the armorial quarterings on the tomb at [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham, West Suffolk]], for Lewknor's son, but the heraldry was optative. There was, however, direct de Braose descent on Lewknor's maternal (Copley) side.</ref>  \n\nLewknor was elected a Member for Horsham to the Parliament of March 1553, jointly with the younger [[Henry Hussey (died 1557)|Henry Hussey]] of [[Slinfold]].<ref>For a referenced account of the Husseys of Slinfold, see R.J.W. Swales, 'Hussey, Henry (c.1484\u20131541) of Slinfold, Sussex' and 'Hussey, Henry (c.1520\u201357) of Slinfold, Sussex', in 'Local Politics and the Parliamentary Representation of Sussex 1529\u20131558' (PhD Dissertation, University of Bristol 1964), Vol. 2, [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/29029355.pdf pp. 269\u201376 (pdf p. 279)].</ref> John Michell of Stammerham had been in tenure of High Barns in 1548, and was so still in May 1553, when Lewknor granted to him and his heirs the lands called New Park in Beeding.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Edward VI'', V, pp. 73\u201374 (28 May 1553).</ref> The accession of Queen Mary followed on 6 July. Thomas Wroth, a signatory to the Letters supporting [[Lady Jane Grey|Jane Gray]]'s succession, attended the King's deathbed and assisted in the proclamation of Mary, but was briefly imprisoned: soon afterwards he escaped to Italy, expecting worse consequences, and did not return to England until 1558.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> Lewknor remained a royal servant (by Machyn's account, groom porter), and received a commission for the peace, but he did not remain in Parliament. John Michell succeeded to his seat for Horsham in October 1553, but within the next year the Duke of Norfolk, being rehabilitated, challenged Michell's title to the New Park.<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 1/1360/57. It was further questioned by the Crown in 1571: E 134/13Eliz/East4.</ref> Neither Michell nor Lewknor is known to have sat in Parliament again.\n\n==Treason==\nLewknor was not overtly implicated in [[Wyatt's rebellion]] of 1554 (incited by Mary's decision to marry King Philip II of Spain): he was lent a corslet from the Tower armoury to oppose it.<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> However, as Dorothy Lewknor was cousin-german to Jane Hawte, Wyatt's wife, there was room for suspicion. It was in the aftermath of the executions of Wyatt and of Jane Gray and [[Guilford Dudley]], and in the context of the Marian persecutions, that Lewknor allowed his position within the royal household to be exploited as part of a more widespread resistance. With a group of sympathetic gentlemen, [[Henry Dudley (conspirator)|Henry Dudley]] planned to raise an army of Englishmen exiled in Europe, and with assistance from the King of France to land in England and rally enough support to depose the Queen and instal Elizabeth as monarch. France however made a truce with Mary, so to fund the project an attempt was made to steal \u00a350,000 in Spanish silver from the Queen's exchequer. In the process, on 18 March 1555/6 the plot was revealed, and several involved were imprisoned in the Tower, racked for confessions and executed between April and July 1556. Dudley however escaped abroad.<ref>J. Bruce (ed.), ''Letters and Papers of the Verney Family down to the end of the year 1639'', Camden Society LVI (London 1853), [https://www.archive.org/stream/letterspapersofv00vernrich#page/58/mode/2up pp. 58\u201376.]</ref><ref>J.A. Froude, ''History of England from the Fall of Wolsey to the Defeat of the Spanish Armada'', 12 Vols, (Longmans, London 1870), Vol. VI, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31175016726500;page=root;view=image;size=100;seq=23;num=1 pp. 1\u201315.] (Hathi Trust)</ref> \n\n[[Henry Peckham (MP for Wycombe)|Henry Peckham]], son of Sir Edmund Peckham (Receiver-general of the Exchequer), on 1 February 1555/6 disclosed the plot to Edward Lewknor and his cousin [[William West, 1st Baron De La Warr|William West]], (heir to the [[Thomas West, 9th Baron De La Warr|9th Baron De La Warr]] but then unable to inherit his title). Prompted by Sir [[Anthony Kingston]], a fellow conspirator,<ref>Kingston's wife Mary Gaynesford was second cousin to Joan Hawte, mother of Thomas and Dorothy Wroth: see Hovenden (ed.), ''The Visitation of Kent'' (1898), pp. 212\u201314.</ref> Peckham asked them to obtain a copy of the Will of King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], by which they hoped to disprove Mary's title to the throne. Lewknor was said to have met with sympathisers in Sussex and London, and to have heard loose talk about an attack on the Queen over a game of cards.<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> He procured a copy of the Will and sent it to West's house within a fortnight, where it was given to Peckham. Both were implicated by Peckham's confession. Lewknor was committed to the Tower of London on 6 June, tried at the [[London Guildhall|Guildhall]] on 15 June, convicted of treason and sentenced to death.<ref>Nichols, ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/108/mode/2up p. 108.]</ref> West was arraigned on 30 June and in an attainder by verdict was also convicted and condemned, but later received a pardon.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls Philip and Mary'', III: 1555\u20131557 (HMSO 1938), pp. 539\u201340. (10 April 1557)</ref> \n\nLewknor was returned to the Tower, but his sentence was deferred. In his confinement Dorothy and one of his daughters were permitted to live with him in his quarters for several weeks. On 7 June Mary had given orders to [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|William Paget]] for the leading exiles (Sir Thomas Wroth heading the list of nine names) to be summoned immediately to England, \"all excuses, delayes, lettes, hindrances and other occasions happening to you whatsoever utterly sett ap[ar]te\", to appear before the King and Queen and privy council on the last day of October to answer such matters as may be objected against them, not failing upon their faith or allegiance.<ref>Letter of Queen Mary to William Paget, 7 June 1556. Sotheby's, Sale of English Literature, History, Children's Books and Illustrations, 12 July 2016, [http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2016/english-literature-history-childrens-books-illustrations-l16404-/lot.6.html# Lot 6.]</ref> During August 1556 Thomas Wroth, then living in [[Strasbourg]], evaded receiving delivery of the summons and instead obtained a permit to become fully resident there.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> Lewknor, who may have hoped for a pardon, sent a message to the Queen praying forgiveness and grace for his wife and children. Frances Malet, priest to Sir [[Henry Bedingfield (1509)|Henry Bedingfield]] (Lieutenant of the Tower of London), took a letter to the Queen about Lewknor, but could not obtain a positive reply. On Sunday 6 September he died without receiving the final [[Viaticum|Sacrament]].<ref>Sir Henry Bedingfield to the Council, 6 September 1556, in A.J. Horwood (ed.), 'MSS of Sir Henry Bedingfield, Bart., at Oxburgh, Co. Norfolk', ''Third Report of the Royal Commission on Historical Manuscripts'' (Appendix), (Command, Eyre & Spottiswoode, HMSO 1872), pp. 237\u201340, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3_sUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA239#v=onepage&q&f=false at p. 239.]</ref> He was buried in the Tower precincts on the following day.<ref>Nichols, ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/114/mode/2up p. 114.]</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nLewknor's plea did not go altogether unheard. At his widow's petition, on 27 February following the Queen restored to her the manor and advowson of Hamsey, together with many lands in Hamsey and Woham (i.e. Offham), which had been forfeit to the crown on account of the attainder. Also the term of years in the manor of Kingston Buci, which had been held for life by Margaret Lewknor since 1538, but had before the time of his attainder reverted to him by his mother's death, was (with the exception of the advowson, fines, heriots, and lands in Henfield) now assigned to Dorothy for a payment of \u00a3200, together with all his goods and chattels.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Philip and Mary'' III: 1555\u20131557 (HMSO 1938), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027026446&view=image&seq=463 pp. 451\u201352] (Hathi Trust). T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue SAS-D/105 (East Sussex Record Office).</ref> The manor was accordingly rated for 'Dorathe Lewkenor' on 12 July 1558 by the Commission for lands sold during that year.<ref>British Library Harleian MS 608, item 118, fol. 70v: ''Catalogue of the Harleian Manuscripts in the British Museum'', Vol. I (Commissioners, Westminster 1808), [https://archive.org/stream/CatalogueOfTheHarleianManuscripts1/Catalogue_of_the_Harleian_Manuscripts_1#page/n437/mode/2up p. 388.]</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of Mary in November 1558 and the accession of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], a new parliament was called on 23 January 1558/9. Among its first actions was the passage of a bill to restore Lewknor's children in blood, lineage and degree, reversing the effect of his attainder. The petition of Edward, Thomas, Stephen and William, and of Jane, Mary, Elizabeth, Anne, Dorothie and Lucrecie, 'sonnes and daughters to Edward Lewknor, late of Kyngeston Bowsey in the Countie of Sussex, Esquire,' addressed to Elizabeth that their father 'in the tyme of your heighnes syster, the Quenes ma[jes]tie that dead is, was attaynted of heighe treason...'<ref>Howard, ''The Visitation of Suffolke'', II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LCgAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA269#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 269.].</ref> It was read in the House of Commons on 3, 10 and 15 March, when it was passed by them, and, being taken to the Upper House on 20 March, it received all three readings on the following day, all these being recorded in the ''Journal'' of Sir [[Simonds D'Ewes]].<ref>S. D'Ewes, revised P. Bowes, ''Journals of all the Parliaments During the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' (John Starkey, London 1682), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vA1DAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 25, 20 & 21 March 1558/9.]</ref>\n\nIn 1588 Dorothy Lewknor, widow of Edward Lewknor, subscribed to the loan raised by Queen Elizabeth at the time of the expected invasion by the Spanish Armada.  She made her will as of Kingston Buci on 1 October 1587, making her son [[Edward Lewknor (died 1605)|Edward]] her executor, and granting to her son Thomas her moiety of lands and tenements in Old Shoreham, and her term remaining in the manor of King's Barns. She refers to an indenture or recognizance made between herself and her 'very good cosens and frends' Sir [[Francis Walsingham]] and Sir [[Henry Cocke]] in 1570. She was generous in remembering the children of her brothers William and Oliver Wroth, and all her own grandchildren, including particularly her godchildren Dorothy Machell (daughter of Mathew and Mary) and Dorothy Lewkenor (daughter of Edward), and godson Thomas Pellett (son of Benjamin and Dorothy). Her will was proved in August 1589.<ref>Will of Dorothye Lewkenor, widow of Kingston Bowsey (P.C.C. 68 Leicester).</ref>\n\n==Children==\nThe children of Edward Lewknor and Dorothy Wroth are shown as follows:<ref>Bannerman, ''Visitations of Sussex'', pp. 25\u201330, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n45/mode/2up at p. 29.]</ref>\n\n*(Sir) [[Edward Lewknor (died 1605)|Edward Lewknor]] (c.1542\u20131605), of [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham Hall]], West Suffolk, married Susan, daughter and coheir of Sir Thomas Heigham,<ref>See J.H., 'Heigham, John (d.1626), of Barrow, Suff.', in P.W. Hasler (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1558\u20131603'' (Boydell & Brewer, 1981), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/heigham-john-1626 History of Parliament online]</ref> of [[Higham, Forest Heath|Higham]], West Suffolk, and his wife Martha, daughter of Sir [[Thomas Jermyn (died 1552)|Thomas Jermyn]] of [[Rushbrooke Hall]]. They had two sons and seven daughters.\n*Thomas Lewknor (died 1598 or 1599), of Court and Buckinghams, Old Shoreham,<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Old and New Shoreham: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex'' Vol. 6 Part 1: Bramber Rape (Southern Part) (V.C.H., London 1980), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt1/pp149-154 pp. 149\u201354.] (British History Online. Retrieved 21 November 2016)</ref> married Judith Bulman, daughter of Thomas Bulman and wife Elizabeth, son of Arthur Bulman of Sussex. Judith was the sister of Joan Bulman, who married Thomas Wroth of Blenden Hall, [[Bexley]], Kent, a son of Dorothy Lewknor's brother Sir Thomas Wroth, and father of [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 17th century)|Sir Thomas Wroth of Petherton Park]]. She had three other sisters.<ref>W. Berry, ''County Genealogies: Pedigrees of the Families in the County of Sussex'' (Sherwood, Gilbert and Piper, London 1830), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=okhFAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA361#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 361.]</ref> Judith remarried to Anselm Fowler.<ref>See ''Fowler v. Bishop'', T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 2/Jas1/F2/45 and C 2/Jas1/F4/9.</ref>\n*Stephen Lewknor, living 1559, died without issue.\n*William Lewknor, living 1559, died without issue.\n*Jane Lewknor, married (1) William Larke, Esq. [will proved 1582], and (2) John Pascall, Esq., of [[Great Baddow|Much Baddow]], Essex (son of John Pascall and Mary Kebyll?).<ref>A 1558 pedigree for Pascall of Much Beddow appears in W.C. Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex in 1552, 1558, 1570, 1612 and 1634'' 2 Vols, Harleian Society XIII-XIV (1878, 1879), I, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofess13metc#page/88/mode/2up p. 88.]</ref> (issue)\n*Mary Lewknor (at marriage, of [[Broxbourne]], Hertfordshire<ref>Perhaps then living near the manor of Beymondhall (Beaumond Hall), [[Cheshunt]], with its appurtenances in [[Wormley, Hertfordshire|Wormley]], property of her uncle [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 16th century)|Sir Thomas Wroth]].</ref>), married by licence dated 1 July 1568<ref>General licence issued 1 July 1568, in J.L. Chester, ed. G.J. Armytage, ''Allegations for Marriage Licences issued by the Bishop of London, 1520\u20131610'' Vol. I, Harleian Society Vol. XXV (London 1887), [https://archive.org/stream/allegationsform01londgoog#page/n45/mode/2up p. 39].</ref> to Mathew Machell (c.1547\u20131593) of Shacklewell in [[Hackney (parish)|Hackney]], Middlesex, son of John Machell ([[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworker]]), Alderman and Sheriff of London (died 1558) and his second wife Joan Luddington, daughter of Henry Luddington, citizen and [[Worshipful Company of Grocers|Grocer]] (died 1531<ref>Will of Henry Lodington, Grocer of city of London (P.C.C. 1531, Drake quire).</ref>), and step-daughter of Sir [[William Laxton (Lord Mayor of London)|William Laxton]]. They had one son, John Machell, gentleman of Hackney, [[Wendover]] and [[Wonersh]] (1580-1647) (who married first, 1599, [[Nicholas Woodroffe#Children|Jane Woodroffe]] and secondly, c. 1624, [[Francis Aungier, 1st Baron Aungier of Longford#Marriage and issue|Lady Elizabeth Aungier]]), and at least three daughters, Dorothy (died 1593<ref>Buried Hackney 13 October 1593: Hackney St John burial register.</ref>), Jane (wife of Henry Welch of Wendover<ref>Will of Henry Welch, Wheelwright, of Wendover, Buckinghamshire (P.C.C. 1651, Grey quire).</ref>), and Elizabeth (wife of John Cave<ref>Married [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham, West Suffolk]], 22 October 1608: S. Hervey, ''Denham Parish Registers 1539-1850, with notes'' (Paul and Mathew, Bury St. Edmunds 1904), [https://archive.org/stream/denhamparishreg00hervgoog#page/n55/mode/2up p. 38].</ref>).<ref>'Machell', in Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex'', I, (Visitation of 1634), [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofess13metc#page/440/mode/2up p. 441.]</ref> Two other daughters, Ann (wife of _____ Gibbs), and Mary (died c. 1635) (married first, 1611, the Revd. Ralph Cudworth (d. 1624), and secondly, c. 1624, the Revd. [[John Stoughton (priest)|John Stoughton]]: mother of [[Ralph Cudworth]] and [[James Cudworth (colonist)|James Cudworth]]), are also attributed.<ref>E. Bellasis, ' 1886, 'Machell of Crackenthorpe', ''Transactions of the Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society'' VIII (1886), 2nd Machell pedigree (from John Machell of London) at end of article, based partly upon a pedigree tradition which is in places confused. Richardson accepts both as of this family: D. Richardson, 'Cudworth', ''Jewels of the Crown'' Newsletter 4 (Fall 2009), pp. 4\u20136, [http://www.charlemagne.org/jewels%2010-29-09.pdf at p. 5.] (see ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (2011), II, p. 10, items 15\u201316).</ref>\n*Elizabeth Lewknor, living 1559.\n*Anne Lewknor, living 1559.\n*Dorothy Lewknor (died before 1590), married (as his 1st wife) (Sir) Benjamin Pellatt, Knt., of [[Steyning]] (Upper Beeding) and [[Bolney]], Sussex.<ref>Bannerman, ''Visitations of Sussex'', [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n169/mode/2up p. 153.]</ref> They had (at least) three sons and one daughter.<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description SAS-M/1/368 (and see 367, 717 and 720) (East Sussex Record Office).</ref>\n*Lucrecie (or Lewcreys) Lewknor (living 1587), married William Jackson of London.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{nobots|deny=InternetArchiveBot}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewknor, Edward (died 1556)}}\n[[Category:1517 births]]\n[[Category:1556 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1553 (Mary I)]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n'''Edward Lewknor''' (c.1517\u20131556) was the representative of a branch of a prominent Sussex family, in an [[armigerous]] line descending in the distaff side from the [[Baron Camoys|Camoys barony]]. Having attained standing as a member of parliament and (reportedly) a position of service in the royal household, his career was ended abruptly by his involvement in [[Henry Dudley (conspirator)|Henry Dudley]]'s conspiracy against Queen [[Mary I of England|Mary I]], and his consequent [[attainder]]. His children were restored in blood by Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]].<ref>For a referenced account of Edward Lewknor, see R.J.W. Swales, 'Lewkenor, Edward (1518\u201356), of Kingston Buci, Sussex', in 'Local Politics and the Parliamentary Representation of Sussex 1529\u20131558' (PhD Dissertation, University of Bristol 1964), Vol. 2, [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/29029355.pdf pp. 288\u2013291 (pdf p. 298)].</ref> \n\n==Family origins==\nEdward Lewknor<ref>R.J.W. Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward (1516/17-56), of Kingston Buci, Suss.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.) ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer, 1982) [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/lewknor-edward-151617-56 History of Parliament online].</ref> was the son of Edward Lewknor (died 1528) of [[Kingston by Sea|Kingston Buci]], Sussex,<ref>D.G.C. Elwes and C.J. Robinson, ''A History of the Castles, Mansions, and Manors of Western Sussex'' (Longmans & Co., London/G.P. Bacon, Lewes), [https://archive.org/details/ahistorycastles00elwegoog/page/n181 pp. 130\u201331].</ref> and his wife Margaret Copley, daughter of Roger Copley [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|citizen and Mercer]] of London and of Roffey (in [[Horsham, Sussex]] - died c. 1482<ref>Admitted to freedom of Mercers, 1456: see L. Jefferson, ''The Medieval Account Books of the Mercers of London: An Edition and Translation'', 2 vols (Ashgate, Aldershot 2009), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Bc8GDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT1105&lpg=PT1105&dq=%22Roger+Cople%22&source=bl&ots=6jrXxcbAww&sig=ACfU3U2sXnnoK1v4NXmKn8u8XNRQfZmxKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbr_G7xNbnAhXFoXEKHUclDxwQ6AEwAHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Cople&f=false Name Index] (Google).</ref>) by his wife Anne, a daughter and coheiress of Sir [[Thomas Hoo, Baron Hoo and Hastings]] by Eleanor, daughter of [[Lionel Welles, 6th Baron Welles|Lionel Welles]].<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'' 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8JcbV309c5UC&pg=RA1-PA9#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 8\u201310] (Google). Sir Thomas Hoo had two daughters named Anne: this was the younger.</ref> Margaret Copley's sister Eleanor was the third wife of [[Thomas West, 8th Baron De La Warr]], who acted as [[Feoffment|feoffee]] for Edward's grandfather in securing the descent and uses of his estates according to the terms of his will.<ref>Will of Edward Lewknor of Kingston Buci (P.C.C. 1528).  Inquisition post mortem: Edward Lewkenor (Sussex), T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 142/47/41 (Chancery).</ref> Edward's father had a younger half-brother Richard Lewknor and three half-sisters, whose mother Anne (died 1538),<ref>Will of Dame Anne Echingham (P.C.C. 1538).</ref> daughter of John Everard of [[Cratfield]] and sister-in-law of John Tasburgh of [[St Peter, South Elmham]],<ref>'Everard' (1), in W. Rye (ed.), ''The Visitations of Norfolk, 1563, 1589 and 1613'', Harleian Society Vol. XXXII (London 1891), [https://archive.org/details/publicationsofha32harluoft/page/116 pp. 116-17] (Internet Archive).</ref> remarried to Sir [[Edward Echyngham]] of [[Barsham, Suffolk]] (died 1527).<ref>Will of Sir Edward Echyngham of Barsham (P.C.C. 1527).</ref><ref>F.H. Suckling, 'Some Notes on Barsham juxta Beccles, co. Suffolk', ''The Genealogist'' XXI (1905), [https://archive.org/stream/genealogist2119selb#page/n269/mode/2up pp. 124-42], 243-50, and XXII (1906), [https://archive.org/stream/genealogist2219selb#page/n123/mode/2up pp. 52-61] (Internet Archive), 128-34, 149-54 and 212-22, '''at''' XXII, pp. 52-61.</ref>\n\n===The Camoys descent===\nHis grandfather, also Edward (died 1522),<ref>Will of Edward Lewkenour of Kingston Bowcy (P.C.C. 1522\u201323). The date of Probate shown in the Register is earlier than the date of the will itself, and should probably read 1523.</ref> was the son and heir of Nicholas Lewknor of Kingston Buci (youngest son of Sir Thomas Lewknor of [[Horsted Keynes]] by Elizabeth Echyngham, stepmother of Baron Hoo and Hastings) and his wife Elizabeth (Isabella) Radmylde.<ref>As shown in the ''Drury Manuscript'', British Library Add. MSS. 5523, fol. 110: see J.J. Howard (ed.), ''The Visitation of Suffolke, made by William Hervey, Clarenceux King of Arms, 1561,'' Vol. II (Samuel Tymms, Lowestoft/Whittaker & Co., London 1871), pp. 261\u201370, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LCgAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA269#v=onepage&q&f=false at p. 269.] W.D. Cooper, 'Pedigree of the Lewknor Family', ''Sussex Archaeological Collections'' III (1850), [https://archive.org/stream/sussexarchaeolo13socigoog#page/n132/mode/2up pp. 89\u2013102, at p. 102.]</ref> Elizabeth and her sister Margaret Radmylde became the coheirs of their nephew William Radmylde, who died without issue. Their mother Margaret Camoys (born c. 1402), first wife of Ralph Radmylde, was granddaughter of [[Thomas de Camoys, 1st Baron Camoys]] (died 1421), and (with her sister Eleanor) coheir to her brother [[Hugh de Camoys, 2nd Baron Camoys|Hugh Camoys, 2nd Lord Camoys]].<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Plantagenet Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), I, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kjme027UeagC&pg=PA471#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 471 ff.]</ref> Eleanor married Sir Roger Lewknor of Broadhurst, elder half-brother of Nicholas Lewknor.<ref>D. Richardson, ed. K.G. Everingham, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (Richardson 2011), III, 'Lewknor', pp. 15\u201321 at pp. 18\u201319, and see [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8JcbV309c5UC&pg=RA3-PA372#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 372.]</ref> Hugh died in 1426, when the title went into abeyance until 1839. It was then resurrected in [[Thomas Stonor, 3rd Baron Camoys]], descendant and heir of Elizabeth Radmylde's sister Margaret, who married John Goring.<ref>C. Clark and W. Finnelly, ''Reports of Cases Heard and Decided in the House of Lords on Appeals and Writs of Error, and Claims of Peerage: During the Sessions 1831[-1846],'' Vol. 6, 1838 & 1839 (V. & R. Stevens and G.S. Norton, London 1842), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GmBGAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA789#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 789\u2013867; see p. 818.]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Hamsey, St Peter's Church.jpg|thumb|right|300|St Peter's church, Hamsey, Sussex]]\nLewknor had a younger brother Anthony and sisters Eleanor, Mary and Barbara.<ref>W. Bruce Bannerman, ''The Visitations of the County of Sussex... in 1530 and 1633\u201334, etc.'', Harleian Society LIII (London 1905), [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n45/mode/2up pp. 25\u201330, at pp. 28\u201329.]</ref> According to an Inquisition upon his father's death,<ref>Chancery, C 142/47/41.</ref> Edward was then 11 years old. His father's will, however, left estates including [[Hamsey]] (East Sussex) in feoffment to mature for him in October 1542. Other estates including Kingston Buci were allocated to Anthony, and were in the administration of the widow and three other executors, and with the assistance of Sir Roger Copley, during minority. Margaret Lewknor assumed sole responsibility as [[executor]] but Edward came into the wardship of one of the co-executors, Robert Wroth of Durrants, [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]] (Middlesex), and of [[Gray's Inn]]<ref>Autumn reader, 1528: J. Foster, ''The Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn, 1521\u20131889'' (Hansard, London 1889), [https://archive.org/stream/registerofadmiss00gray#page/2/mode/2up p. 2.]</ref> (from 1531 attorney of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] and M.P. for Middlesex 1529\u20131535), a descendant of Sir Roger Lewknor and Alianora Camoys.<ref>'Wroth of Enfield', in G.J. Armytage (ed.), ''Middlesex Pedigrees collected by Richard Mundy'', Harleian Society LXV (1914), [https://archive.org/stream/middlesexpedigre651914#page/16/mode/2up p. 17.] Richardson, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', III, p. 372.</ref>\n\nRobert Wroth's eldest son [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 16th century)|Thomas Wroth]] was of a very similar age to Edward Lewknor.<ref>H. Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas (1518\u201373), of Durants, Enfield, Mdx. and London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wroth-thomas-1518-73 History of Parliament online]</ref> The Wroth household was of Protestant sympathy: Robert Wroth became a friend of [[Thomas Cromwell]]'s, and from 1534 until his death two years later Wroth shared with Cromwell the stewardship of Westminster Abbey.<ref>H. Miller, 'Wroth, Robert (1488/89-1535), of Durants, Enfield, Mdx.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wroth-robert-148889-1535 History of Parliament online]</ref> Thomas was sent to [[St John's College, Cambridge]], but did not take a degree.<ref>J. & J.A. Venn, ''Alumni Cantabrigienses'' I.iv (Cambridge University Press, 1927), [https://archive.org/stream/p1alumnicantabri04univuoft#page/468/mode/2up pp. 468\u201369.]</ref> At his father's death in 1536 he became a ward of the Crown, and in that year he entered Gray's Inn.<ref>Foster, ''Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn'', p. 11.</ref> It is claimed (but does not appear) that Lewknor was admitted in the same year.<ref>R. Chapman, 'The Parochial History of Hamsey', ''Sussex Archaeological Collections'' XVII (George P. Bacon, Lewes 1865), pp. 70\u2013103, [https://archive.org/stream/sussexarchaeolo21socigoog#page/n106/mode/2up at p. 79.]</ref> Cromwell at once obtained a grant of the marriage and wardship of Thomas Wroth,<ref>J. Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic'', Henry VIII, Vol. XI (HMSO 1888), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol11/pp349-378 943: Grants October 1536 (item 6).]</ref> and in 1538 sold the marriage to [[Richard Rich, 1st Baron Rich|Sir Richard Rich]], who arranged that Thomas should marry his daughter Mary Rich.<ref>Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers'', Henry VIII, XIV (ii), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol14/no2/pp303-358#highlight-first Miscellaneous: December 1538 & May 1539, p. 324]; XV, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol15/pp251-300#highlight-first 613: Grants April 1540 (item 9)], [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol15/pp325-349#highlight-first 733: Grants May 1540 (item 64)]. (British History Online)</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nThe wardship and marriage of Edward were granted to his mother in May 1533.<ref>Gairdner, ''Letters and Papers, Henry VIII'' VI, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol6/pp234-262#highlight-first 578: Grants May 1533 (item 37).]</ref> However Robert Wroth in his will written in 1535 explicitly required that his ward Edward Lewknor should marry his daughter Dorothy: if either were to refuse or mislike the match, Dorothy was to have the financial benefit arising from the dissolution of the wardship.<ref>Will of Robert Wroth of Durrants, Enfield (P.C.C. 1536).</ref> Edward and Dorothy were accordingly married. Dorothy's mother Jane was the daughter of Sir Thomas Hawte (a [[William Hawte|Woodville]] descendant), who had died in 1505, and his wife Isabel (Elizabeth) Frowyk, sister of [[Thomas Frowyk|Sir Thomas Frowyk]].<ref>R. Hovenden (ed.), 'De Haut', ''The Visitation of Kent taken in the years 1619\u20131621 by John Philipot and William Camden'', Harleian Society XLII (London 1898), pp. 212\u201314, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationofkent00camd#page/214/mode/2up at p. 214.]</ref><ref>Richardson, ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', II, p. 9.</ref> The union reinforced existing ties of kinship among the numerous posterity of Sir Thomas Lewknor, and reinvested two Camoys lines. The manor of Kingston Buci was in 1537 settled upon Margaret Lewknor for life with an additional twenty years' tenure with remainder in tail male to Anthony Lewknor. Anthony was admitted to Gray's Inn in 1542.<ref>Foster, ''Register of Admissions to Gray's Inn'', [https://archive.org/stream/registerofadmiss00gray#page/8/mode/2up p. 15.]</ref>\n\nMargaret Lewknor lived until at least 1551,<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece descriptions Holmes, Campbell & Co/983 and /1084 (West Sussex Record Office).</ref> and was no doubt instrumental in arranging the marriages of Edward's sisters. Eleanor became the wife of Giles Sentbarbe, Rector of Hamsey c. 1541\u20131555.<ref>Church of England Clergy database: Giles or Egidius Sayntbarbe, Sentbridge, Senbar, etc.: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/locations/index.jsp?locUnitKey=14358 parish of Hamsey.]</ref> Mary married John Michell the younger of Stammerham (in Horsham),<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Horsham: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex''  Vol. 6 Part 2: Bramber Rape (North-Western Part) Including Horsham, (V.C.H., London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt2/pp156-166#anchorn264 pp. 156\u201366.]</ref> a resident of Horsham, whose parliamentary connections may have assisted Lewknor's own ambitions.<ref>R.J.W. Swales, A.D.K. Hawkyard, 'Michell, John II (died 1555), of Stammerham, Suss.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: The House of Commons 1509\u20131558'' (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/michell-john-ii-1555 History of Parliament online.]</ref> Lewknor's sister Barbara married Sir John Dawtrey.\n\n==Progress==\n[[file:Primero.jpg|right|thumb|''Four Gentlemen of High Rank Playing Primero'' (16th century).]]\nThe marital existence of Edward and Dorothy Lewknor was fruitful, producing ten children,<ref>S. D'Ewes, ''The Journals of all the Parliaments During the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vA1DAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49, col. 2, 3 March 1558/9.] Howard, ''Visitation of Suffolk'', II, p. 269, note.</ref> of whom the eldest of the four sons, Edward, was born c. 1541\u201342. It is inferred that the elder Edward entered the service of the [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]].<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament''.</ref> He is suspected to be the Lewkenor, one of the Duke's gentlemen, who in December 1545 came to blows with [[Thomas Hussey (died 1558)|Thomas Hussey]] of Caythorpe, M.P., treasurer to the Duke, while gambling at cards 'at Domyngo's house' in a game of [[primero]].<ref>S.M. Thorpe and T.M. Hofmann, 'Hussey, Thomas I (by 1509\u20131558), of Halton Holegate and Caythorpe, Lincs.', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), \"The History of Parliament: The House of Commons 1509\u20131558\" (Boydell & Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/hussey-thomas-i-1509-58 History of Parliament online.]</ref> The affray occurred at Tothill Fields behind the old [[Palace of Westminster#Old Palace|Palace of Westminster]]: Hussey was reprimanded by the [[Privy Council]], since parliament was sitting at the time, and he (and perhaps also Lewknor) ought to have been there. Both men were briefly committed to the [[Fleet prison]].<ref>S.E. Lehmberg, ''The Later Parliaments of Henry VIII'', 1536\u20131547 (Cambridge University Press, 1977), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MhY9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA228#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 228.]</ref>\n\n[[Henry Machyn]] stated Edward Lewkenor to have been [[Groom Porter]] to King [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]],<ref>J.G. Nichols (ed.), ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', Camden Society Old Series XLII (London 1848), [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/108/mode/2up pp. 108, 114.] Machyn calls him 'master Lecknolle'.</ref> a fact lacking positive confirmation from other sources. (This office included responsibility for royal games at cards). Thomas Wroth, who was knighted in 1547, was successively Gentleman Usher to the Prince's Chamber (1541\u20131547), [[Gentleman of the Privy Chamber]] (1547\u201349) and a principal Gentleman (1549\u201353) to the King: he was also [[Knight of the Shire]] for [[Middlesex (UK Parliament constituency)|Middlesex]] in the parliaments of 1547, 1549 and March 1553.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament online''.</ref> Lewknor is likely to have gained his position in the royal household through his brother-in-law's connections and the influence of Richard Rich.\n \n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Bramber Castle.jpg|thumb|right|300|Bramber Castle seen by [[Wenceslas Hollar]] (1607\u20131677)]]\nIn 1548 Margaret Lewknor was the demesne lessee of the manor of High Barns at [[Upper Beeding]], Sussex,<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Upper Beeding: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex''  Vol. 6 Part 3: Bramber Rape (North-Eastern Part) Including Crawley New Town, (V.C.H., London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt3/pp34-37#anchorn19 pp. 34\u201337.] (British History Online. Retrieved 19 November 2016)</ref> a property seized by the Crown from the attainted Duke of Norfolk, which had been granted to [[Thomas Seymour, 1st Baron Seymour of Sudeley|Thomas Seymour]] in 1547. Following Seymour's attainder in 1549, on 21 May 1553 it, together with the site of the former [[Bramber Castle]] and the disparked lands called Le Newe Park at Upper Beeding were granted in chief by the King to Edward Lewknor, King's Servant, Esquire, for the fortieth part of a knight's fee and in consideration of \u00a3718.8s.8d paid to Sir Edmund Peckham on behalf of the King.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Edward VI, V: 1547\u20131553'' (HMSO, London 1927), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027026412&view=image&seq=108 p. 102] (Hathi Trust).</ref> Lewknor was also granted the house of the former Butler Chantry ''cantarista'' in Horsham, and several tenements appertaining to it, in free socage. The acquisition of the site at Bramber was no doubt a visible assertion or impropriation of Lewknor's perceived [[William de Braose, 1st Lord of Bramber|de Braose]] ancestry or forebears.<ref>Lewknor was descended from [[Thomas de Camoys, 1st Baron Camoys]] (died 1421). The ''Liber Drury'' Lewknor pedigree represents the mother of Camoys as Margaret Foliot (daughter of Joan de Braose), and his paternal grandmother as Margaret de Braose, wife of Ralph de Camoys (died 1336). In both cases Camoys is now understood to have been descended from other wives than these. De Braose is included in the armorial quarterings on the tomb at [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham, West Suffolk]], for Lewknor's son, but the heraldry was optative. There was, however, direct de Braose descent on Lewknor's maternal (Copley) side.</ref>  \n\nLewknor was elected a Member for Horsham to the Parliament of March 1553, jointly with the younger [[Henry Hussey (died 1557)|Henry Hussey]] of [[Slinfold]].<ref>For a referenced account of the Husseys of Slinfold, see R.J.W. Swales, 'Hussey, Henry (c.1484\u20131541) of Slinfold, Sussex' and 'Hussey, Henry (c.1520\u201357) of Slinfold, Sussex', in 'Local Politics and the Parliamentary Representation of Sussex 1529\u20131558' (PhD Dissertation, University of Bristol 1964), Vol. 2, [https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/29029355.pdf pp. 269\u201376 (pdf p. 279)].</ref> John Michell of Stammerham had been in tenure of High Barns in 1548, and was so still in May 1553, when Lewknor granted to him and his heirs the lands called New Park in Beeding.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Edward VI'', V, pp. 73\u201374 (28 May 1553).</ref> The accession of Queen Mary followed on 6 July. Thomas Wroth, a signatory to the Letters supporting [[Lady Jane Grey|Jane Gray]]'s succession, attended the King's deathbed and assisted in the proclamation of Mary, but was briefly imprisoned: soon afterwards he escaped to Italy, expecting worse consequences, and did not return to England until 1558.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> Lewknor remained a royal servant (by Machyn's account, groom porter), and received a commission for the peace, but he did not remain in Parliament. John Michell succeeded to his seat for Horsham in October 1553, but within the next year the Duke of Norfolk, being rehabilitated, challenged Michell's title to the New Park.<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 1/1360/57. It was further questioned by the Crown in 1571: E 134/13Eliz/East4.</ref> Neither Michell nor Lewknor is known to have sat in Parliament again.\n\n==Treason==\nLewknor was not overtly implicated in [[Wyatt's rebellion]] of 1554 (incited by Mary's decision to marry King Philip II of Spain): he was lent a corslet from the Tower armoury to oppose it.<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> However, as Dorothy Lewknor was cousin-german to Jane Hawte, Wyatt's wife, there was room for suspicion. It was in the aftermath of the executions of Wyatt and of Jane Gray and [[Guilford Dudley]], and in the context of the Marian persecutions, that Lewknor allowed his position within the royal household to be exploited as part of a more widespread resistance. With a group of sympathetic gentlemen, [[Henry Dudley (conspirator)|Henry Dudley]] planned to raise an army of Englishmen exiled in Europe, and with assistance from the King of France to land in England and rally enough support to depose the Queen and instal Elizabeth as monarch. France however made a truce with Mary, so to fund the project an attempt was made to steal \u00a350,000 in Spanish silver from the Queen's exchequer. In the process, on 18 March 1555/6 the plot was revealed, and several involved were imprisoned in the Tower, racked for confessions and executed between April and July 1556. Dudley however escaped abroad.<ref>J. Bruce (ed.), ''Letters and Papers of the Verney Family down to the end of the year 1639'', Camden Society LVI (London 1853), [https://www.archive.org/stream/letterspapersofv00vernrich#page/58/mode/2up pp. 58\u201376.]</ref><ref>J.A. Froude, ''History of England from the Fall of Wolsey to the Defeat of the Spanish Armada'', 12 Vols, (Longmans, London 1870), Vol. VI, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31175016726500;page=root;view=image;size=100;seq=23;num=1 pp. 1\u201315.] (Hathi Trust)</ref> \n\n[[Henry Peckham (MP for Wycombe)|Henry Peckham]], son of Sir Edmund Peckham (Receiver-general of the Exchequer), on 1 February 1555/6 disclosed the plot to Edward Lewknor and his cousin [[William West, 1st Baron De La Warr|William West]], (heir to the [[Thomas West, 9th Baron De La Warr|9th Baron De La Warr]] but then unable to inherit his title). Prompted by Sir [[Anthony Kingston]], a fellow conspirator,<ref>Kingston's wife Mary Gaynesford was second cousin to Joan Hawte, mother of Thomas and Dorothy Wroth: see Hovenden (ed.), ''The Visitation of Kent'' (1898), pp. 212\u201314.</ref> Peckham asked them to obtain a copy of the Will of King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], by which they hoped to disprove Mary's title to the throne. Lewknor was said to have met with sympathisers in Sussex and London, and to have heard loose talk about an attack on the Queen over a game of cards.<ref>Swales, 'Lewknor, Edward', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> He procured a copy of the Will and sent it to West's house within a fortnight, where it was given to Peckham. Both were implicated by Peckham's confession. Lewknor was committed to the Tower of London on 6 June, tried at the [[London Guildhall|Guildhall]] on 15 June, convicted of treason and sentenced to death.<ref>Nichols, ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/108/mode/2up p. 108.]</ref> West was arraigned on 30 June and in an attainder by verdict was also convicted and condemned, but later received a pardon.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls Philip and Mary'', III: 1555\u20131557 (HMSO 1938), pp. 539\u201340. (10 April 1557)</ref> \n\nLewknor was returned to the Tower, but his sentence was deferred. In his confinement Dorothy and one of his daughters were permitted to live with him in his quarters for several weeks. On 7 June Mary had given orders to [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|William Paget]] for the leading exiles (Sir Thomas Wroth heading the list of nine names) to be summoned immediately to England, \"all excuses, delayes, lettes, hindrances and other occasions happening to you whatsoever utterly sett ap[ar]te\", to appear before the King and Queen and privy council on the last day of October to answer such matters as may be objected against them, not failing upon their faith or allegiance.<ref>Letter of Queen Mary to William Paget, 7 June 1556. Sotheby's, Sale of English Literature, History, Children's Books and Illustrations, 12 July 2016, [http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2016/english-literature-history-childrens-books-illustrations-l16404-/lot.6.html# Lot 6.]</ref> During August 1556 Thomas Wroth, then living in [[Strasbourg]], evaded receiving delivery of the summons and instead obtained a permit to become fully resident there.<ref>Miller, 'Wroth, Thomas', ''History of Parliament Online''.</ref> Lewknor, who may have hoped for a pardon, sent a message to the Queen praying forgiveness and grace for his wife and children. Frances Malet, priest to Sir [[Henry Bedingfield (1509)|Henry Bedingfield]] (Lieutenant of the Tower of London), took a letter to the Queen about Lewknor, but could not obtain a positive reply. On Sunday 6 September he died without receiving the final [[Viaticum|Sacrament]].<ref>Sir Henry Bedingfield to the Council, 6 September 1556, in A.J. Horwood (ed.), 'MSS of Sir Henry Bedingfield, Bart., at Oxburgh, Co. Norfolk', ''Third Report of the Royal Commission on Historical Manuscripts'' (Appendix), (Command, Eyre & Spottiswoode, HMSO 1872), pp. 237\u201340, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3_sUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA239#v=onepage&q&f=false at p. 239.]</ref> He was buried in the Tower precincts on the following day.<ref>Nichols, ''The Diary of Henry Machyn'', [https://archive.org/stream/diaryofhenrymach00machrich#page/114/mode/2up p. 114.]</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nLewknor's plea did not go altogether unheard. At his widow's petition, on 27 February following the Queen restored to her the manor and advowson of Hamsey, together with many lands in Hamsey and Woham (i.e. Offham), which had been forfeit to the crown on account of the attainder. Also the term of years in the manor of Kingston Buci, which had been held for life by Margaret Lewknor since 1538, but had before the time of his attainder reverted to him by his mother's death, was (with the exception of the advowson, fines, heriots, and lands in Henfield) now assigned to Dorothy for a payment of \u00a3200, together with all his goods and chattels.<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Philip and Mary'' III: 1555\u20131557 (HMSO 1938), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027026446&view=image&seq=463 pp. 451\u201352] (Hathi Trust). T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue SAS-D/105 (East Sussex Record Office).</ref> The manor was accordingly rated for 'Dorathe Lewkenor' on 12 July 1558 by the Commission for lands sold during that year.<ref>British Library Harleian MS 608, item 118, fol. 70v: ''Catalogue of the Harleian Manuscripts in the British Museum'', Vol. I (Commissioners, Westminster 1808), [https://archive.org/stream/CatalogueOfTheHarleianManuscripts1/Catalogue_of_the_Harleian_Manuscripts_1#page/n437/mode/2up p. 388.]</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of Mary in November 1558 and the accession of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], a new parliament was called on 23 January 1558/9. Among its first actions was the passage of a bill to restore Lewknor's children in blood, lineage and degree, reversing the effect of his attainder. The petition of Edward, Thomas, Stephen and William, and of Jane, Mary, Elizabeth, Anne, Dorothie and Lucrecie, 'sonnes and daughters to Edward Lewknor, late of Kyngeston Bowsey in the Countie of Sussex, Esquire,' addressed to Elizabeth that their father 'in the tyme of your heighnes syster, the Quenes ma[jes]tie that dead is, was attaynted of heighe treason...'<ref>Howard, ''The Visitation of Suffolke'', II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LCgAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA269#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 269.].</ref> It was read in the House of Commons on 3, 10 and 15 March, when it was passed by them, and, being taken to the Upper House on 20 March, it received all three readings on the following day, all these being recorded in the ''Journal'' of Sir [[Simonds D'Ewes]].<ref>S. D'Ewes, revised P. Bowes, ''Journals of all the Parliaments During the Reign of Queen Elizabeth'' (John Starkey, London 1682), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vA1DAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 25, 20 & 21 March 1558/9.]</ref>\n\nIn 1588 Dorothy Lewknor, widow of Edward Lewknor, subscribed to the loan raised by Queen Elizabeth at the time of the expected invasion by the Spanish Armada.  She made her will as of Kingston Buci on 1 October 1587, making her son [[Edward Lewknor (died 1605)|Edward]] her executor, and granting to her son Thomas her moiety of lands and tenements in Old Shoreham, and her term remaining in the manor of King's Barns. She refers to an indenture or recognizance made between herself and her 'very good cosens and frends' Sir [[Francis Walsingham]] and Sir [[Henry Cocke]] in 1570. She was generous in remembering the children of her brothers William and Oliver Wroth, and all her own grandchildren, including particularly her godchildren Dorothy Machell (daughter of Mathew and Mary) and Dorothy Lewkenor (daughter of Edward), and godson Thomas Pellett (son of Benjamin and Dorothy). Her will was proved in August 1589.<ref>Will of Dorothye Lewkenor, widow of Kingston Bowsey (P.C.C. 68 Leicester).</ref>\n\n==Children==\nThe children of Edward Lewknor and Dorothy Wroth are shown as follows:<ref>Bannerman, ''Visitations of Sussex'', pp. 25\u201330, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n45/mode/2up at p. 29.]</ref>\n\n*(Sir) [[Edward Lewknor (died 1605)|Edward Lewknor]] (c.1542\u20131605), of [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham Hall]], West Suffolk, married Susan, daughter and coheir of Sir Thomas Heigham,<ref>See J.H., 'Heigham, John (d.1626), of Barrow, Suff.', in P.W. Hasler (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1558\u20131603'' (Boydell & Brewer, 1981), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/heigham-john-1626 History of Parliament online]</ref> of [[Higham, Forest Heath|Higham]], West Suffolk, and his wife Martha, daughter of Sir [[Thomas Jermyn (died 1552)|Thomas Jermyn]] of [[Rushbrooke Hall]]. They had two sons and seven daughters.\n*Thomas Lewknor (died 1598 or 1599), of Court and Buckinghams, Old Shoreham,<ref>A.P. Baggs, C.R.J. Currie, C.R. Elrington, S.M. Keeling and A.M. Rowland, 'Old and New Shoreham: Manors and other estates', in T.P. Hudson (ed.), ''A History of the County of Sussex'' Vol. 6 Part 1: Bramber Rape (Southern Part) (V.C.H., London 1980), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt1/pp149-154 pp. 149\u201354.] (British History Online. Retrieved 21 November 2016)</ref> married Judith Bulman, daughter of Thomas Bulman and wife Elizabeth, son of Arthur Bulman of Sussex. Judith was the sister of Joan Bulman, who married Thomas Wroth of Blenden Hall, [[Bexley]], Kent, a son of Dorothy Lewknor's brother Sir Thomas Wroth, and father of [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 17th century)|Sir Thomas Wroth of Petherton Park]]. She had three other sisters.<ref>W. Berry, ''County Genealogies: Pedigrees of the Families in the County of Sussex'' (Sherwood, Gilbert and Piper, London 1830), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=okhFAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA361#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 361.]</ref> Judith remarried to Anselm Fowler.<ref>See ''Fowler v. Bishop'', T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description C 2/Jas1/F2/45 and C 2/Jas1/F4/9.</ref>\n*Stephen Lewknor, living 1559, died without issue.\n*William Lewknor, living 1559, died without issue.\n*Jane Lewknor, married (1) William Larke, Esq. [will proved 1582], and (2) John Pascall, Esq., of [[Great Baddow|Much Baddow]], Essex (son of John Pascall and Mary Kebyll?).<ref>A 1558 pedigree for Pascall of Much Beddow appears in W.C. Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex in 1552, 1558, 1570, 1612 and 1634'' 2 Vols, Harleian Society XIII-XIV (1878, 1879), I, [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofess13metc#page/88/mode/2up p. 88.]</ref> (issue)\n*Mary Lewknor (at marriage, of [[Broxbourne]], Hertfordshire<ref>Perhaps then living near the manor of Beymondhall (Beaumond Hall), [[Cheshunt]], with its appurtenances in [[Wormley, Hertfordshire|Wormley]], property of her uncle [[Thomas Wroth (politician, 16th century)|Sir Thomas Wroth]].</ref>), married by licence dated 1 July 1568<ref>General licence issued 1 July 1568, in J.L. Chester, ed. G.J. Armytage, ''Allegations for Marriage Licences issued by the Bishop of London, 1520\u20131610'' Vol. I, Harleian Society Vol. XXV (London 1887), [https://archive.org/stream/allegationsform01londgoog#page/n45/mode/2up p. 39].</ref> to Mathew Machell (c.1547\u20131593) of Shacklewell in [[Hackney (parish)|Hackney]], Middlesex, son of John Machell ([[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworker]]), Alderman and Sheriff of London (died 1558) and his second wife Joan Luddington, daughter of Henry Luddington, citizen and [[Worshipful Company of Grocers|Grocer]] (died 1531<ref>Will of Henry Lodington, Grocer of city of London (P.C.C. 1531, Drake quire).</ref>), and step-daughter of Sir [[William Laxton (Lord Mayor of London)|William Laxton]]. They had one son, John Machell, gentleman of Hackney, [[Wendover]] and [[Wonersh]] (1580-1647) (who married first, 1599, [[Nicholas Woodroffe#Children|Jane Woodroffe]] and secondly, c. 1624, [[Francis Aungier, 1st Baron Aungier of Longford#Marriage and issue|Lady Elizabeth Aungier]]), and at least three daughters, Dorothy (died 1593<ref>Buried Hackney 13 October 1593: Hackney St John burial register.</ref>), Jane (wife of Henry Welch of Wendover<ref>Will of Henry Welch, Wheelwright, of Wendover, Buckinghamshire (P.C.C. 1651, Grey quire).</ref>), and Elizabeth (wife of John Cave<ref>Married [[Denham, St Edmundsbury|Denham, West Suffolk]], 22 October 1608: S. Hervey, ''Denham Parish Registers 1539-1850, with notes'' (Paul and Mathew, Bury St. Edmunds 1904), [https://archive.org/stream/denhamparishreg00hervgoog#page/n55/mode/2up p. 38].</ref>).<ref>'Machell', in Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex'', I, (Visitation of 1634), [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofess13metc#page/440/mode/2up p. 441.]</ref> Two other daughters, Ann (wife of _____ Gibbs), and Mary (died c. 1635) (married first, 1611, the Revd. Ralph Cudworth (d. 1624), and secondly, c. 1624, the Revd. [[John Stoughton (priest)|John Stoughton]]: mother of [[Ralph Cudworth]] and [[James Cudworth (colonist)|James Cudworth]]), are also attributed.<ref>E. Bellasis, ' 1886, 'Machell of Crackenthorpe', ''Transactions of the Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society'' VIII (1886), 2nd Machell pedigree (from John Machell of London) at end of article, based partly upon a pedigree tradition which is in places confused. Richardson accepts both as of this family: D. Richardson, 'Cudworth', ''Jewels of the Crown'' Newsletter 4 (Fall 2009), pp. 4\u20136, [http://www.charlemagne.org/jewels%2010-29-09.pdf at p. 5.] (see ''Magna Carta Ancestry'', 2nd Edition (2011), II, p. 10, items 15\u201316).</ref>\n*Elizabeth Lewknor, living 1559.\n*Anne Lewknor, living 1559.\n*Dorothy Lewknor (died before 1590), married (as his 1st wife) (Sir) Benjamin Pellatt, Knt., of [[Steyning]] (Upper Beeding) and [[Bolney]], Sussex.<ref>Bannerman, ''Visitations of Sussex'', [https://archive.org/stream/visitationsofcou5354beno#page/n169/mode/2up p. 153.]</ref> They had (at least) three sons and one daughter.<ref>T.N.A. Discovery Catalogue, Piece description SAS-M/1/368 (and see 367, 717 and 720) (East Sussex Record Office).</ref>\n*Lucrecie (or Lewcreys) Lewknor (living 1587), married William Jackson of London.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewknor, Edward (died 1556)}}\n[[Category:1517 births]]\n[[Category:1556 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1553 (Mary I)]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "twk", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Lewknor_(died_1556)"}
